animal.description:
Lana is a diabetic and 7 years old please read entire bio and serious inquires only she needs a hero. Only experienced adopters please that know what it is like to take care of a diabetic animal.  

Meet sweet Lana- we rescued her from the local kill shelter about a month ago for having a very low body score meaning she was too skinny. Well it turns out she is diabetic and requires insulin shots every 12 hours - and then you wait a half hour after fed to give it to her. 
Sometimes it requires two people to help hold her. She’s about 7 pounds and should be 10 pounds. She is strong willed with other dogs small and large and holds her ground if she’s picked on. She has separation anxiety and can not be kenneled due to her urination due to diabetes or she would lay in urine.  We are working on her potty habits and doggie door. She loves to be held and sleeps all night in the bed with you.  She does not like to be babygated she would bark.  She needs a yard and easy fast access to get outside - no apartments or condos as she is very vocal.  I feed her farmers dog and dry food called ketonatural.  She is still going to the vet for glucose curves and still needs spayed.  So if you are willing to put forth the effort to give Lana the safe loving environment that she needs with a very secure yard and financially able to help her please call Mandi at (702) 321-0578 with Ahome4spot of Diana at 702-239-7986. 
She is a lifetime commitment and was a stray the rest of her life she deserves to be treated like a queen. Slight bision loss do to the diabetes.

Sent from my iPhone.  Mandi Dawson ??

animal.description:
Hi all, my name is River but my friends call me Big Papa! I am a 7 yr old neutered male Bulldog Mix weighing in at just about 80lbs. I am a big boy who loves to run and play, and take nice long walks in the woods. Oh, and I love snuggling up in my blanket too. I create the cutest little cocoon and only have my head poking out- my friends say its adorable, I say its comfy and warm.

I am a big boy and will need a strong owner who can take me for lots of walks and keep me mentally and physically stimulated. And I do need a home all to myself- no kids, cats, dogs, or other animals (please no chickens!!)- but I promise to fill your heart and home with tons of love! Oh and an experienced owner is necessary too. I don't like sharing my stuff so I need someone who has worked with doggos like me before.

Did you fall in love with my goofy smile and charming personality? Give my friends at the Saratoga County Animal Shelter a call to learn more about me! Meets by appointment only. 518-885-4113

animal.description:
Hello! My name is Franklin the Two Dimensional Hound. I am about 3.5 years old.
My looks are deceiving. I may LOOK like a tall, handsome fawn Great Dane, but I am, in fact, basically a cat crossed with an anxious blonde. Don’t let that turn you off...I am quite entertaining, and I do love my people. Don’t feel bad for my svelte frame, either - I choose this. A fella’s gotta watch their figure, dontchaknow. (Ever seen Zoolander? It’s not just the females.) I don’t want to be chunky, so I make sure I skip a few meals to keep this lean figure. 

So...I don’t really care much to interact with most other dogs...because OBVIOUSLY I was born in the wrong body, and am a cat. I like to rub on you, back and forth...it’s my favorite. I also like to pretend I want to come in for affection, but then coyly turn away at the last minute so you can’t actually pet me (this is one of my favorite cat tricks... it amuses me to watch the people roll their eyes and throw their hands up in exasperation. Ha ha!) 

And water?? OMG. *trembles delicately* Even drinking it offends me. Ugh. Why do we even have to do the “water” thing? Ew ew ew. Dewy grass is so gross, too. Sometimes my foster mom makes me go potty IN THE RAIN and UGH.  I’m super sensitive about...well, pretty much everything. You’re all offensive and I find you mostly contemptible, nerve wracking, and bleh...you gotta give me a minute to “warm up” to you... But I CAN do it. 

I would be super comfortable in a home with other cats like me, but NO DOGS. Well, maybe I’d consent to an alpha female, but that’s it, ok? Dogs are so gross. But I love other cats. 
I get along really well with chickens and stuff too because they’re not scary
 
My favorite friend in the house is an orphaned kitten who’s a month old...he likes me, too. He’s not very scary. Usually. Sometimes he bites my toes or swats at my face and I run and hide in my crate, but I AM NOT SCARED, I just...you know. I was tired of playing anyway, and stuff. 
My mom laughs because he’s a pound and a half, but he’s got sharp things *literally everywhere* and omg I can’t risk marring this handsome face, or my beautiful deer-like feet. 

I am looking for a home with very strong adults who won’t let me push them around. No first time dog owners for me!

So, here’s what my “foster mom” has to say: Frank would do best in a home as an only dog but is very adaptable to all other animals. He has been compatible with a large alpha female but is still “learning how to dog” politely, so his adopters need to be a bit dog savvy if wanting to add him to a home with another dog. He would do best in a home with older kids, and an experienced owner - he definitely needs his human to be a calm, confident leader who won’t let him get away with every whim. His exercise needs are remarkably low, though he does love to run...he isn’t a dog who will drive you crazy bouncing off the walls. He can take a little time to warm up to men, but always comes around shortly if you’re polite and gentle.  
He is so very sweet and loving, and endlessly amusing with his antics.

Dogs – case by case
Cats- yes
Kids – 12+

Update Nov 17

Hello again! Franklin the Two Dimensional Hound here. I am not called that because of my personality, you see (because I am rather complex), but because I’m a lean mean svelte machine (by choice, thankyouverymuch). 

So, a lot has happened since I checked in with you all last. I’ve become a fully functioning member of the pack here, and I have to say...I’m a lot more relaxed this way. But my foster mom has a unique pack, and I’m also pretty needy...so I’d really prefer to just have a larger alpha female friend, please. Sharing is sometimes annoying. 

My best friends here are actually the orphaned kittens my foster mom has been taking care of. She doesn’t need to remind me often to be “easy”...I think I understand now. Mostly. The bigger cats still make me a little nervous, but when they’re friendly, that’s really nice. 
Sometimes I still like to tease the goats here, but they’re ouchy - those horns hurt. I leave the chickens alone still because foster mom says so. 

I recently met a neighbor dog - really cute standard poodle - and we took a walk together, and I had so much fun! Foster mom says we should do it again, and maybe even give a doggy daycare a shot for the “socialization” (?). I mean I’m pretty okay with dogs that aren’t trying to, you know...share things I don’t want to share. Foster mom makes sure they don’t harass me when I have a bone or food or anything, and that makes me happy. 

Did I mention I get along well with cats? I feel like this may be important. Also, because I think I may be half cat, myself. Dogcestry.com says they don’t really test for that, but I’d like to believe I’m just a super tall cat. 

You have to be patient with me - disruptions in my routine are kind of upsetting, and sometimes it kills my appetite/upsets my tummy. I would really appreciate a quieter home without a lot of activity, though I am getting super gracious with visitors. They’re not so scary! Foster mom never lets anyone scary mess with me, and I think I know this now, so even strange men are okay after I can have a few good sniffs. 

Foster mom says I’d benefit from “going to school”, too. Formal “training” ?. SHE thinks it would help me be happier, but ...well maybe it would. Maybe I would give it a shot. 
Anyway, although I’m pretty happy now, I know this isn’t my forever place. Would you be interested in a tall, sensitive blonde? I’m really super fun and delightful when I’m comfortable somewhere ??? And, if I might say so myself, I’m pretty gosh darn handsome, to boot.

Update 1/8/21

Happy New Year, from Frankie!

Frank’s all about some “New Year, New Me”. Well, sort of. He’s made amazing strides with his social skills & now is trusted with the pack even when not directly supervised. Yes, even the tiny dog!

He’s learned appropriate corrections, also. Although his foster mom takes every precaution to avoid triggers like food or high value bones, every once in a while one of the small animals slips through a gate unnoticed & gets a little too close for his liking. Would he make contact, he could really hurt a 2 1/2 pound annoying kitten, but he doesn’t. 

It’s really amazing how wonderful and respectful he is with cats - he grew up with no small animals, and would chase cats in the yard in his original home. He also spends most of his time “denning” with the miniature dachshund in the home, which is reinforcing his respect for and bond with smaller dogs.

We do feel his options are broadening, as far as what he can live in harmony with. So far...pretty much everything, as long as the other creature isn’t easily intimidated. He’s still an opportunist and can be a little bit of a bully if the other animal cows to him, but if the cat/dog/hedgehog/goat/chicken on the other end stands up to him when he gets pushy, he backs off. 

His options for dogs he can click with are definitely broadening. His foster family thinks he would be a great candidate for a savvy doggy daycare, to further hone the wonderful social skills he’s learning.  Formal obedience classes are highly recommended (and will be a requirement for his adoption) for Frank! Not only has he never been taught any formal commands (we are making slow progress on this), but a class would both increase his social skills through positive exposure and provide his new person with guidance when he or she inevitably gets stuck. Also, it’s a wonderful bonding experience and increases confidence in both dog and handler!

We are looking forward to Frank finding his forever home, so he can complete his growth as a more balanced pup. We feel he’ll leave much/most of his anxiety behind, once in a place where he fits in a little better (there are a lot of critters he’s expected to coexist with around here! He would prefer less lol). 

Frankie is silly, fun, loving, gentle, and a wonderful companion. He’s also a tall drink of water and turns heads everywhere he goes! He turned 4 on Thanksgiving, and is a healthy and athletic dude.


MAGDRL only adopts to approved adopters in NY, NJ, PA MD, DE, D.C.,VA and WV. We are not able to cover full states in some cases. Please check the individual states website for more information on area coverage.

animal.description:
Armani came to us neglected and in need of emergency medical help. Despite living the first year or so of her life tied to a porch, she has proven to be an overcomer. Armani has so much love to give! She craves attention and will do everything she can to crawl in your lap for cuddles and kisses. Armani weighs 43 lbs at 2 years of age. She loves to play (and destroy) toys, and will play fetch until your arms are worn out!  Armani is currently being fostered with 4 big dogs and has done well.  Armani is still very puppy-like in her behavior and can be domineering while playing so a non-dominant dog companion would be ideal. Given that she is still very mouthy, she would be better suited for a family without small children. Due to her breed, Armani has a high prey drive and has not done well with small dogs (she has not been cat tested).  Armani is housebroken and crate trained (she does not willing go in her crate but once in, settles quickly). She does great on a leash, and loves going for walks. Pictures just don't do this girl justice! Armani is the perfect mix of calm, playful and loving! 

Please visit halfwaythererescue@gmail.com for information on meeting and/or adopting Armani!

animal.description:
Angel is a pretty 7 month old black and rust girl with natural ears and a docked tail. She weighs about 60lbs now, so she’ll likely to be a good size when she’s mature. Angel was turned into a shelter by elderly owners who could not handle her. She had no training what so ever in her previous home. 
She is very smart and she is responding well using positive training methods. Angel is learning basic obedience cues and how to walk on leash. Angel easily becomes over stimulated/aroused, and then will jump, mouth your hands and run non-stop around the house. Angel is being heavily reinforced for calm behaviors, and this is how she eats her meals throughout the day, as result Angel is starting to make better choices. Although, she is making great strides she still has a ways to go. House training is going well, because Angel is taken out often. Tossing a tasty treat will get Angel into her crate, although she does protest at times especially if her people are moving around the house. Angel happily gets into the car and she rides fairly well. 
Angel will need to be exposed to new things at her own pace and one where she can be successful. Angel requires a fenced in yard (no electric fence). The ideal home for Angel will be a calm structured household with owners who are experienced with working breed dogs. She’ll need an owner who is patient, consistent and fair. Someone who understands the importance of both mental stimulation and physical activity. If not challenged mentally, Angel will find her own fun and that likely will not be appreciated. Angel would likely do well with scent work, tricks or some other type of dog activity. Angel likes other dogs, but she can be obnoxious and off putting to other dogs, so she will be placed as an only dog. She deserves to have someone committed entirely to her and provide what she’s missed out on in her early months. 
DAR&E places dogs in MD, DC, VA and parts of WVA only.  
If you are interested in this pet please follow the link below to read about our adoption process and submit an adoption application.  (copy and paste)  
https://www.dobe.net/adoption/adoption-process/

animal.description:
**ADOPTION PENDING **

Hello!

 My name is Jovie and I am a 4 1/2 year old green-eyed American Bulldog/Mastiff mix.

 My favourite things are walk time, dinner time, and cuddle time. I am a total sweetheart and very affectionate with my foster humans. I love to get silly rolling around on the carpet and stretching out real long.

 I am super strong and athletic (my foster mom thinks I'd be great at agility), but content with a couple walks per day and a run in the yard. My ears do this adorable thing where they get stuck back when I run, because they are so floppy. I still have some work to do on my leash walking as I can get a little over stimulated when there is lots going on and forget to walk nicely. But my foster mom says I have made good progress and keep getting better as I get more acclimated to the sniffs, sights and sounds around me. I am a quick learner and love training time because I am very food motivated and enjoy any time spent with my humans.

 While at home I'm pretty easy going, quiet and happy to chill out and nap while my foster parents are working and doing other boring things. I follow my humans around the house and don't like being left alone, but if you hang out with me for a bit while I chill in my crate I should be ok when you leave the house (though the pandemic has meant that my foster parents are usually around). I am house broken and sleep through the night in my crate without a peep, and though I prefer if the crate is near my humans I can probably learn to sleep on my own with a little patience. 

 I enjoy meeting new people and am good with strangers, but it's best to take it slow because I can be a little nervous. Spend a few minutes cuddling me or giving me treats and I'll be your best gal. I do not have very good doggie social skills. I have had success making friends with slow introductions and distanced walks, but I am hyper stimulated when meeting dogs for the first time and don't know how to play safe. I would do best in an environment without other dogs, or with an owner who is experienced in managing new relationships. I am apparently good with kids, but haven't met too many.

 Did I mention how pretty I am? Oh yeah, I get complimented on my looks all the time, no big deal. Just one look into these green eyes and you'll know what I'm talking about.

- Jovie is being fostered in Toronto
- we will be reviewing applications after her dental on Jan 18th

animal.description: Daisy is a stocky low rider, 5 years old and 60 lbs. of love, who is a bit nervous when she first meets new people. She clearly wasn’t treated well early on but she warms up quickly and becomes a goofy, wiggly cuddle bug. This girl loves to cuddle. She’d lie on top of you if you let her. Daisy wants to please and listens well and learns the rules quickly. She is potty trained and mellow in the house and gets along wonderfully with the other female dog and friends dogs that she has been introduced to. She can be aggressive to dogs outside her home or pack so she will need to be on leash or in a yard at all times. She does have some separation anxiety but does well with bones or toys to chew while you are gone. She doesn’t know her own strength and wants to play with excited kids and can knock them down so she will be best in a home with no small kids.  If you are interested in knowing more about Miss Daisy please email hellopittyrescue@gmail.com and include your phone number.

animal.description:
Meet this sweetie named Lexie! She came in mid December 2020 when her owner could no longer keep her. She is 9 years old, current on shots, already spayed, and missing her home life setting. Owner told the shelter she can be selective with her canine friends but is a love and super sweet girl. She’s happy and loves going for walks and playing in the runner at the shelter. She will run after a tennis ball when thrown but doesn’t always retrieve it. Loves soaking up body rubs and affection and so deserves a loving FOREVER home to enjoy her “golden years” being pampered and loved. Maybe you have the most amazing loving FOREVER home for Lexie?! Visit with her today! 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

animal.description:
Meet this sweetheart named Harker! She came into the shelter January 2, 2021 when her owner could no longer keep her or her sister Hattie. We were told they were both pulled from a not good situation and we’re nursed back to good health...we’re super underweight. They have been great at the shelter. Super loving and sweet and have “separately”played with a few other male dogs and have been good. The owners said they didn’t always get along which is common with sibling pups. They did say she can be protective of her people when other dogs come up for attention. She is hyper and is jumpy  but very typical of the breed. She is kennel trained and enjoys playing fetch with a tennis ball. She can be an escape artist is left unattended outside. She enjoys chewing and digging so keeping toys around for her to enjoy playing with is good. She’s scared a little of loud  noises and thunder.  Owner recommended a home without other animals but said she was good with older children since she is jumpy and could knock a little kid down not intentionally. Harker is pretty new and sometimes we see behaviors the longer they are there or maybe it was a situational issue within the living arrangements, or maybe just be separated away from her sister will clear the issue of a home without other animals. She’s been super friendly and loving. Stop by for a visit with Hattie today and adopt her into your heart and home! 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. animal.description:
Happy Jack
2 years old, 50 pounds
Pit Bull Terrier Mix

Happy Jack came to our southern partner rescue several months ago, after they received a call about an emaciated Pit Bull tied to a telephone pole in a dangerous part of Jackson, MS. He had a chemical burn all the way down his back and he also had heartworm. 

He’s really sweet and he is always happy, thus the name. He is full of of energy and just wants to play. Jack has been in boarding for almost 5 months now so it is way past time for him to be in a home. He deserves so much better than living in a kennel. He has completed heartworm treatment and is now 4dx negative.  

Jack would make a great adventure or hiking companion! He does have a lot of energy! Jack is kennel trained and plays well with other dogs. He plays really hard so he needs another dog his size who loves to play as much as he does. He does great around kids, older kids would be best due to his high energy. And no cats please. He would do best having a fenced yard or be adopted by some who runs a lot! 

Due to COVID-19 travel restrictions, we are only accepting applications from residents in ME, NH and VT." 

Adoption Fee: $450 (this covers previous expenses of the dog- appropriate vaccinations, altering, microchipping, and transportation fees.)

animal.description:
IMPORTANT!!!!! FOREVER HOME MUST HAVE A FRIENDLY, PLAYFUL AND CONFIDENT RESIDENT DOG!

MEET CONNER, an handsome, friendly and fun-loving 10 month old, 45lb lab mix looking for a loving home preferably with a experienced and active guardian and a friendly, non-senior, playful resident dog. Conner is with an awesome foster mom who has lots of good stuff to share about this fabulous pup:

"Conner is a very sweet and cuddly boy who loves ear scratches, back scratches and bum scratches too. He is very loving and affectionate and melts like butter when you rub his belly A 15-week-old puppy is his best friend and he is so good with her despite being four times her size--he's very patient and gentle and loves playing with her. Being only 10 months old, he's a good listener, a quick study and highly treat and praise motivated. Training the two of them is great fun! He's a smart dog, and is crate and leash trained and housebroken. He loves chewing on Kong toys (and most anything left on his floor), playing with stuffed animals, being outside (but not alone) and running around. He's got the right amount of energy for a 10-month-old boy. He's adventurous and will make an awesome hiking or jogging buddy. He is also very sweet with Lacey who has high anxiety and who's not very playful. He will benefit from ongoing training and confidence building exercises. He's a very sweet pup who is going to make an awesome companion."

He is neutered and up to date on age-appropriate vaccines. His adoption fee is $425. Please note that training is highly recommended for all dogs. As with all rescue animals, breed determination cannot be validated without genetic testing.

THANKS FOR ADOPTING AND SAVING A LIFE; you are CONNER'S hero!

*MUST HAVE RESOURCE GUARDING AND BITING EXPERIENCE. PLEASE READ & MEET ALL REQUIREMENTS BELOW PRIOR TO APPLYING*

Remy is a 7-year-old, 80 lbs, labradoodle/goldendoodle mix is looking for his forever family. He is UTD, neutered, chipped, housebroken, crate trained, and learning to walk well on a leash. Remy is low energy and would love a family to cuddle and snuggle with while having some fun adventures in the process with. He is good with dogs but unsure about cats. Remy has resource guarding behaviors that can be managed with e-collar corrections. However, he does find anything as a high-value item that he will guard; from trash to poop to toys. Experienced home that will provide structure and work with a training plan provided by the trainers through the rescue can help manage and improve these unwanted behaviors.

Remy has to find my new forever home because his current owners do not have the expertise on resource guarding to properly handle and manage it. 

Adoption requirements:


	Owned a dog with prior resource guarding issues 
	Willingnenss to continue training that will be provided by HTAR 
	No kids (under 18)
	MUST reside in the greater Orlando area for training support


Please note, Remy is part of Happy Trails Animal Rescues rehoming program. She has not been tested or evaluated and the information gathered is from the current owners personal statements regarding health and temperament. The owner is subject to placement outside of our organization. We cannot guarantee availability.

Sammy is about 14 months old. He was pulled from the shelter with a broken leg. We amputated the leg and we have been preparing Sammy for family life.

Sammy was definitely abused and he has been in a foster home with another dog, he is cat friendly and is slow to trust people.

Sammy is lovely when you become part of his pack. He navigates around on three legs like a pro. He loves walks both on and off leash. He loves to chase squirrels and belly rubs.

We know Sammy is going to need to be in a home with a patience family. He loves older kids, and other dogs. He is approximately 55lbs and he has no idea he only had three legs.

Everyone who has met Sammy had fallen in love. He just has to love you! Sammys wish list. Someone who does not give up, loving, is patience, loves to walk, and loves to give belly rubs.

Sammy does come with a bean bag, his security blanket. No bean bag, no deal!!

Sammy is fully vaccinated and neutered and comes with only 3 legs! 

Sammy is fully vaccinated


If you are interested in adopting this dog, please review our adoption process and then fill out an online adoption form at https://www.calpaws.org/adopting. Experience with obedience training is definitely preferred. We are a small rescue and do not have the resources to respond to inquiries. If a dog is our website, it is still available. We can not arrange meet & greet without an application.

We are always in need of fosters for the amount of dogs we have coming in. Being a foster is such a rewarding experience. If you are interested please review https://www.calpaws.org/fostering

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Hero. I'm a a very sweet, 3 year old, 72lb. male GSD who's just settling in at my foster home. In my previous life, I lived in a home with older children and a female GSD, but unfortunately I was not given much training and was allowed to get out, soooo I made some bad choices. That's how I ended up in the shelter. Right now I'm just trying to figure out what's expected of me. I'm great with people. and other dogs, but I'm not a fan of cats at all. I am house trained and I am working on crate training. I love to ride in the car and play with a ball. While here, I'm working on Place, Sit, waiting through thresholds and walking on a loose leash. I attended the EDH pack walk and did well with the people and some 25 plus dogs that walked with us. I can get excited when I see another dog, but all you have to do is remind me, and I redirect well. I'm actually pretty calm. All I really want is to be with my person. I'm a very quick learner and would love to be in a structured house with a GSD saavy family and another dog to play with. Could you be my forever home? More to come on me once I've had time to adjust to my new surroundings. I'm neutered, heartworm negative, microchipped and current on vaccinations. Minimum adoption donation: $350.00

animal.description:
RJ has had a rough time of it in his short life as you can see by his face. What happened to him exactly is still not clear to us. He was living tied up outside and clearly not given the best care. He's very nervous at the shelter and very very slow to make up to people.. RJ will not be a social butterfly anytime soon so he's looking for a quiet home to learn how to be part of a family inside a home. We haven't learned a lot about RJ yet as he's so nervous still. A home with adults only or teenage children that is calm and can give RJ a lot of time to decompress and come around to his new people would be best. RJ is believed to be a pit bull mix of about 2 years old. He weighs 66 lbs and as you can see has some physical healing to do yet. 

We have no way to test for cat or other small animal compatibility. However, we do offer a 5 day foster-to-adopt program to those who live within an hour of Chillicothe, OH. This will allow you time to figure out if this dog is compatible for you. If not, simply bring the dog back and if it's a great fit you just come back and adopt. 

If you are interested in one of our dogs please go to rosscountyhumanesociety.org and fill out the online application. Once approved we will contact you to schedule an appointment to meet the dog.RCHS does not conduct DNA tests on dogs who enter our facility therefore we are unable to guarantee breed or breed mix. Information provided by shelter staff, volunteers, and veterinarians is used to give a best estimate as to a dog's breed make up. We do our best to inform adopters about the potential breeds for each dog.

We are a dog only facility so we do not know how most of our dogs will be with cats. Even if a dog is surrendered to us and said to be good with cats there is no way to be sure the dog will be good with your cats. We do have a 7 day foster-to-adopt program so that you can see how the dog interacts with your cats before adoption.

animal.description:
Midgie: She is a 5 year old Chihuahua Dachshund mix. We are looking for a home with no other dogs because she would prefer to be an only dog. She is good with kids and cats. She is mostly house trained but will have accidents on occasion when she is too stiff to get outside on time. She has been very neglected by her previous owners but has made alot of improvements, last year she suffered a tear to her hip muscle and has some trouble walking, but has been making alot of progress in her physical therapy. She is more of a lap dog but laying around causes her to get stiff and she needs help to get back up. Her nails are overgrown but with constant grooming appointments they should get back to normal. She does not like to play with toys but loves her chew bones and a nice bed to curl up on or even laying on the sofa. Overall she loves people but will need extra care.

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting this baby, please fill out an application. They currently are fixed, up to date on shots, wormings, preventatives and are microchipped. Adoption fee is $188 ($175 Adoption Fee + $13 Lifetime Registration Fee for Microchip), applications can be filled out at this link. https://www.petstablished.com/adoption_form/10167/generic .We cannot guarantee breed or size when full grown.

Due to our current situation, with more great applicants than we have available puppies and young adults, we are no longer accepting applications from people that are over 150 miles away. Exceptions will be made on dogs over the age of 3, special needs dogs and direct referrals from our volunteers.

animal.description:
Hi there, Im Orville (like the Wright brother or the popcorn guy) and Im happy to now live in Colorado. I am told I am one of the most handsome dogs. I am looking for my forever home and promise to be the best dog possible. I am around 1 years old and only 45 pounds. I was found hanging around a Knights of Columbus office in Texas and was taken to a shelter. After being excited to get my own home and people, I became more and more sad that no one came and brought me to a home of my own. I know that coming to Colorado is my chance to find a home of my own that I can share with a loving family

 

While I have been adjusting to being in a loving home, I have needed some extra TLC. I have been good with other dogs and some older children (11 & 14) while I adjust to being cared for. Im happy in my kennel as I have found it to be a good place to feel safe and secure.


NOTE: After arriving at the shelter in Texas, staff noticed that Orville had a limp and although he didn't have a pain response, they performed x-rays anyway. It appears that he may have experienced past trauma to his left pelvic area.

animal.description:
Meet Minerva a.k.a. Minnie

 

Sweet, sweet Minnie jumps right into your heart as soon as you meet her. Literally everyone we spoke with at 2BABR about Minnie said, I love her! We agree. Whats not to love? Shes a beautiful German Short-haired Pointer mix who wants to jump right into your heart. Shes great with the kids and loves affection, particularly having her belly rubbed.

 

Weighing in at 53lbs shes a wiggling, waggly bundle of affection. We dont know much about Minnies past - she was rescued from a shelter in New Mexico and is about 3 years old. Shes recovering beautifully from being spayed upon arrival in Colorado. 

 

Shes inquisitive and wants to see everything Im up to in the kitchen, but responds well to correction when I remind her not to be so nosy. She prances proudly on walks and responds well to my direction when weve encountered other dogs. She travels well in a harness in the car and her tail wags wildly when she greets the kids (ages 9,11, and 14).

 

She didnt know what to make of the kennel at first, but were working together to help her feel it is her safe space. And now she will gladly go into it in order to eat her dinner and sleep at night. And she has good house manners!

 

Minnie would make a beautiful addition to any family that wants to love a dog as much as she loves you!

 

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)

animal.description: Elroy is a go-with-the-flow kind of guy. Do you want to go for a walk? Hey, he's with you. Would you rather go for a car ride? Sure. Do you need help with your yard work? He's glad to help, or just bask in the sun. And if you want to talk to him, he's happy to listen and then come to you for some loving. His slow-wagging tail will warm your heart. This well-mannered senior boy is sharing his foster home with five other dogs, and he just hangs out with them. The cats in his foster home he either ignores - or naps with them. He's also really good with small children, greeting them and wandering off. He's also a wonderful leash walker and rides well in the car's front seat, gazing out the window, so happy to see cows. At home, Elroy is content to be in the same room with his people, coming up for some loving with his slow tail wag. And then he's happy to go find his bed for long naps. He understands and obeys all commands, and he's a house-trained boy who will go in a crate, but doesn't need to. He's free to roam the house and does well when home alone. Elroy's age has brought some teeth and vision problems, and he needs eye medication twice a day. He will do best in a quiet, slow-paced home where he can have short walks and long naps - and loving. Come meet him. He'll be your lovable and perfect roommate!

animal.description: It's getting' cold outside, so why not have someone to snuggle up with? Issa surely fits the bill! She's currently living with an APA foster family and would love to join your home. Issa likes to keep things simple. Her preferred activities are going for walks and snuggling up with her favorite people! She's always on the lookout for affection. She'd love to be a lap dog all day. Since cuddling can't fill up a whole day, Issa also likes to head out for exercise. She's been getting the hang of leash walking with her foster family, and will be ready to head out for a stroll with you. In her foster home Issa has been doing well with the older children in the home, and she likes to play with the dog next door. She can be shy when meeting new people but usually warms up quickly. She will go right into her crate, and is working on her basic obedience commands. We've found Issa to be playful, gentle, and loving. She likes some activity each day but mostly wants to be with you. She would enjoy sharing a home with children, but would do best as the only pet until she settles in and receives a bit more training. She has all the makings of a fantastic long-term companion for your family. And don't forget, when you adopt from APA you won't just be giving Issa a good home - you'll also be helping the next dog who can join us!

animal.description: French Toast is such a smart boy and a fast learner! He's already learned that humans are wonderful and he greatly benefits from snuggling with them! Now that he's living with them, he's already learned that they let him roll around in the yard and play with toys. Wow! This very strong and energetic boy has recovered from an injury to his leg and hip, and now he loves to run off at warp speed for a sprint in the garden, and is ready to start learning about leash walking. He also is so happy to feel safe in a home. He still has some separation anxiety and wants to be with his people all the time, eager to be their absolute sweetheart and get their attention. He's also living with two other Boxers, and has shown no aggression to them. And he's doing well with the fosters' 12-year-old and teenage kids. French is a very curious, playful and mischievous boy who has begun to understand some requests from his people, and he seems ready to begin learning from their training. And he's a house-trained boy who's doing well in his crate (as long as he can chew his toys). He's also an affectionate boy who comes out in the morning and leans on his people. This highly energetic, loving young boy hopes to be the only pup in a home with equally energetic, active and patient adults and older teenagers who can continue his training and a yard to run and roam. Come meet him, for sure, he'll want to be your new best friend!

animal.description: Despite his regal name, King Triton appreciates the simple things in life - playing with his toys, snuggling, and most of all, being with his people. Whenever you're together, KT (as he's affectionately called) will curl up at your feet or stretch out on a nearby dog bed and chill. If and when you're ready to play, he can cut loose and be a goofy boy. You couldn't ask for a more adoring companion, with obedience skills to boot! King Triton is living with separation anxiety, a debilitating panic disorder that can be improved in a majority of cases with the right tools. To KT, there is nothing scarier than the thought of being alone. When he does, he might bark or cry and is destructive. APA! is seeking a qualified adopter to help KT have a chance at a happy life and improve his mental health by working closely with a veterinarian and a professional behavior team that will guide the adopter through a customized training program with the support of behavioral medication. It is critically important that an adopter rearrange their lifestyle to prevent KT from actually being alone for at least the first few months of his life in his new home. Even being away for more than 5 minutes might be too much for him to tolerate at first, but in time with the right professional support - and a village of volunteers to help the adopter cover absences - he will learn to tolerate absences. This will require creativity and dedication. But as the saying goes, it takes a village, and this boy has one! APA! has a devoted group of volunteers who can watch him when friends, family, neighbors and other creative solutions fall short. An ideal home for King Triton would be one with only adults or mature teenagers, low traffic, a yard to romp in, and a patient, caring person willing to put in the extra work to treat and manage his separation anxiety at first. He might be able to live with a well-matched dog - he has a lady dog friend at APA!. In exchange for helping him through this, you will get the devoted companion of a lifetime. Inquire about adopting today and come meet this handsome boy! Follow the life and times of KT on Instagram @adopt_my_friends_at_apa!.
animal.name: King Triton

animal.description:
PLEASE READ: You MUST visit https://www.save-a-mutt.org/adoption-application/ to fill out an application and get pre-approved before meeting any Save-A-Mutt dogs. We are a foster based rescue. There is no facility to visit. 

This face, those grey whiskers.....we love this guy.  Charles is a sensitive boy who is ready to find his forever family.  He would love a family that will include him in outdoor adventures like hiking, swimming, running and walking.  He is strong and he is learning how to walk on a leash.  Charles just wants to please his people which will make him very easy to train.

Charles has spent time with other dogs and would do well with a calm doggie friend who will teach him how to relax and enjoy life. He tends to be protective of his people and another confident dog will help him learn when to protect and when to relax. Charles loves to spend time outside and will need a home with a securely fenced yard. No apartments for this big boy.
This guy is very playful and might think it's fun to chase the resident cat so any cats in the home should be dog savvy.

Charles recently received a dental and had a gingival mass removed.  The mass was benign.  He had many fleas when he was rescued and had quite a bit of hair loss because of that.  It is recommended that his adopter continue with soothing baths as needed to keep his skin healthy and aid in the continued growth of his coat.  
Charles is 10 years old and weighs 75 pounds.

Adoption fee is $150.00
Save-A-Mutt is a registered 501c3.

Please note, we have approximately a 300 mile adoption radius. We don’t ship dogs, once approved you must pick them up in Snohomish County, WA *Due to the Border Closure to Canada - we are currently not accepting Canadian Adoption Applications*. Sorry.

I would love to be included in family activities because I love being with my humans. I would probably do best with a family with older kids because of my size, and I'd love to have another dog to romp with.

Snapshot of Amethyst!

Interested? Learn more about Amethyst below!

Hi! I'm Amethyst! I'm a super enthusiastic female boxer mix, about two years old. I was with a foster in Texas originally and made the long journey to now be with one in Minnesota! I am a mama dog and had a litter of puppies about three months ago. I have tons of energy and love to spend my days going on walks and playing tug of war, but also napping and cuddling up to my people. I don't live with a second dog at the moment but don't have any problems with other canines - the one next door and I communicate often with a single bark on each side, as acknowledgement!

I'm what the humans call "super sweet"- there's nothing I love doing more than snuggling up with my person on the couch or on the bed, with a fluffy blanket. I do have my own bed and it's alright, most of the time - give me the couch any day, though! I am still learning the concept of personal space; but my foster mom says I'm getting better at it, slowly but surely. I do know a few tricks and can do them without treats - I sit, lay down (occasionally), give paw, and stay quite well. My foster mom taught me to sit before my leash is put on and taken off before and after we go out on a walk. I also know to sit and wait while my food is dished out - I don't eat until I hear the word "okay", and I'm quite proud to say I do it well! I am a very good kennel dog- I walk into my crate with no problems and will curl up there when told. I do have a hard time keeping quiet when I know it's time to go out, or - on occasion - when I see my foster mom doing things around the room that I really, really want to help out with. I'm working on that, though! I'm also quite good with food - I don't ever steal food off my foster mom's plate or grab food out of her hands. I'm more a believer in the method of sitting by her with my puppy eyes and hoping I get a reward for being good! Walks are my favorite part of the day (after cuddles) and I love to be outside. I do get cold easily so my walks aren't very long :) I believe the world is a great big wonderful place that needs to be explored so I am quite an enthusiastic walker, walking ahead of my foster mom and being sure to check out every sight and smell before she does. I do pull occasionally- come on, which dog doesn't?- when there is something that absolutely needs my immediate attention, like a squirrel or a human passing by or a fellow canine. Again, that's something I'm working on, day by day! I absolutely love curling up next to my people and will put my head on their laps or right by theirs just to show them how much I love them. I am still learning to love the car - I get very anxious when the car is moving, so I'm looking for a family that can help me learn that the car is a safe space!

I get attached to my people very easily and tend to like to follow them around everywhere because it is imperative that I keep an eye on them, just to make sure they're safe. With that being said, I would love to be a part of a family that has more than one person for me to shower my love on! I also sometimes get afraid of being alone, so being in a family would help me to get used to both cuddle time and alone time with every person there. I do have a ton of energy and sometimes forget just how big I am so my foster mom thinks that I should definitely be supervised when around kids. However, I am a great listener and a quick learner so can adapt really well to my forever home's lifestyle
!

About Amethyst:

Adoption Fee: $450

*Foster to Adopt: I am looking for a forever home now, but I still need to be spayed! So, I'm looking for a family that will be able to commit to bringing me to my spay appointment on
Saturday, Feb 13th.

TCPR will be responsible for this

appointment as long as my new family will bring me to it!

Then once medically cleared, I'll be fully ready to be adopted!

Please consider saving the life of an animal in need and become a volunteer foster home today. To become a foster, fill out a dog or cat foster application on the Twin Cities Pet Rescue website: www.twincitiespetrescue.org . There is little to no cost to foster an animal. Twin Cities Pet Rescue provides its foster families with food, supplies, and veterinary care for its animals. All you need to do is supply the love!

Oprah
Female
1 year old in February 
Australian Shepherd 
Approximately 45 pounds
Blind
Potty trained 
Crate trained
Good with other dogs on a limited basis. Needs a submissive play buddy or only dog
No experience with cats but don’t think she would do well
 Shouldn’t be with small children. Could knock down, easily excitable and somewhat reactive if startled
 Located near Johnstown/ New Albany

I am an 11-month old girl with lots of puppy energy. My foster mom says I am super sweet and a very good girl with a few quirks mostly as a result of my blindness. I do best with a structured day so I know what to expect and I love my CBJ oil! Barking is my primary communication method since I am totally blind. I don’t bark much while out of my crate unless I am playing, not sure what or who is around, or if I hear a strange sound on TV. I haven’t been around cats but my foster mom says she doesn’t think it would be a good idea to live with one. I also shouldn’t have small kids around since I cannot see and have so much puppy energy. I don’t want to bump into them or scare them if I bark because I am not sure who they are.
 
My ideal home will have a fenced yard and neighboring or visiting playful dogs but I would do best as an only dog. An apartment or condo where neighbors are sharing walls isn’t a good place for me since I bark when first put in my crate or when I am startled. With all of my puppy energy, I really need to get lots of play time. Squeaky toys and ropes/toys where you or another playful dog can play tug with me are my favorites. The fenced yard will allow me freedom to run, sniff and play without restriction and help build my self-confidence. Walks are good, but not enough exercise for me. When I get tired of playing outside and listening to the birds and neighborhood sounds, I go to the back door to come back in the house.
 
My foster mom likes it when I want to be pet because I literally back up and sit on her foot. I have just started giving her kisses while she pets me. I am learning house manners very fast now that I am comfortable in my foster home. No house accidents for over a month and I keep my crate clean when mom has to leave the house. My foster mom has started giving me Kongs with frozen peanut butter and those things are the bomb!  I am microchipped, spayed and up to date on shots. I would love to have my own home. Please contact Speak if you are ready for a fun and energetic girl.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please review our adoption policies and apply online at [www.speakfortheunspoken.com/adopt](http://www.speakfortheunspoken.com/adopt).

Visit [www.speakfortheunspoken.com](http://www.speakfortheunspoken.com/) will give you more information about our rescue.

***PLEASE READ*** WE DO NOT RESPOND TO PETFINDER OR EMAIL INQUIRIES. Please fill out an application on our website if you are interested in adopting this dog. We will only set up a meeting with the dog once you have an approved adoption application. We actively manage our dogs on Petfinder, the dogs listed are available for adoption. We will remove the dog from view once they are pending adoption.

Cookie is an approximately 1 year old female Lab, possibly hound? mix. She was rescued from a Kentucky shelter when her time was up. Unfortunately for Cookie she is very scared and shy. She is trying really hard to trust people and is getting lots of extra love and attention by staying up in the treatment kennels with our technicians always near by with peanut butter and toys. Onyx is a model citizen here... keeps a clean kennel and does not even bark when we walk in and out for let outs, etc. He stands calmly at the kennel door waiting to go outside or get attention. 3. Meet the Pet
Additional Adoption Info
Adoption Requirements

• Must be 21 years of age or older to adopt a cat, 23 years of age or older to adopt a dog.

• Must provide a copy of your lease agreement or association by laws if you live in an apartment, condo or townhouse

• Must provide documents/receipts that specify your cat or dog’s immunizations/required tests are current (rabies, distemper and fecal (+ for dogs- heartworm test and bordetella if adopting a dog) (+ for cats - leukemia test/vaccine if adopting a cat)). We can call your veterinarian to get this information, if you don’t have the documents. If you know they are not current, bring the animals with you and can have them updated by the animal hospital that houses HSP.

• All adults in the household must be present and co sign the adoption agreement.

• All your currently owned dogs/cats must be spayed or neutered. This is a non-negotiable requirement.

• Heartworm prevention for dogs must also be purchased at the time of adoption and prices vary depending on the size of the animal being adopted.

• Puppies under 6 months old are required to sign up for a puppy obedience class. ($89 deposit required, refundable upon completion)

Each Adoption Includes:
• Spay or neuter surgery
Vaccines current to the date of adoption *:
• Rabies vaccine
• Bordatella vaccine for dogs
• Canine Influenza vaccine for dogs
• Booster for canine and feline distemper and several other dangerous diseases
• Fecal test
• 1st deworming
• Heartworm test (dogs +6 months old)
• Leukemia test for cats
• Capstar flea treatment
• Microchip identification implant
* Boosters required for puppies and kittens (depending on age) POST adoption are the responsibility of the pet owner.

Application Process

Once you have decided on an animal, you will be provided with an Adoption Questionnaire which requires name, address, phone numbers and asks some questions about your household, why you want a pet and how you plan to care for it. The Adoption Questionnaire needs to be approved by an authorized humane society volunteer. If an authorized volunteer is on site, that occurs quickly and if you’ve provided all required information on applicable lease agreements/association by laws and current immunizations/tests for any existing pets, you may be able to take your new friend home immediately. If an authorized volunteer is not on site, you’ll receive a phone call when the status is determined.

Adoption Donations

Adoption donations for adult dogs range from $59 to $399 and puppies from $159 to $599.
Adoption donations for adult cats range from $29 to $99 and kittens from $59 to $399.

We are a private pet rescue and are not affiliated with any government or national organization, and as such our adoption donations are set to cover as much of the cost for the spay/neuter surgery, vaccinations, tests and medical care of our animals that is realistic. We lose money on every animal we take in as our adoption donations are less than what caring for the animals actually costs us. We ask more for puppies, kittens and purebred adults to help cover the expenses of the older mixed breed animals for which we receive minimal donations and incur significant debt. However, even at our highest prices, puppies and kittens are still half the price of pet store animals AND our animals are already altered and up to date on vaccinations.

Post Adoption Care

If you choose to give one of our deserving homeless animals a second chance at a good life, a New Pet Health Assurance Program provided by our partner veterinary clinics is available. This will cover the cost of treating shelter related illnesses should one occur, for 60 days after your adoption date up to $500. If you do not purchase this coverage, you would assume total financial responsibility for any needed medical treatment immediately after you adopt.


Since 2000, we have placed over 10,000 animals into loving homes. Each one of these animals was given shelter, food, medical aid and vaccinations and time to find the right home. Our doctors mended mutilated limbs and cured many illnesses so that these animals could get a second chance at good lives. We have grown and now operate out of 4 locations, not all of them in Plainfield. In 2008 we changed our name from the Humane Society of Plainfield to Help Save Pets, still HSP.

What exactly does HSP do?
We rescue desirable and healthy adult dogs and cats from pounds and shelters in mostly rural areas.

• Many government funded pounds and shelters, especially in rural areas, have an abundance of homeless animals and scarce cage space to house them. The demand for pets from these shelters is low and the kill rate is high.

We rescue puppies and kittens that most rescues will not.
• Many shelters, including other no kill rescues, will NOT take puppies or kittens under 3 months old because of their susceptibility to illness. Most are sadly put to death.

We rescue dogs and cats with curable health problems.
• Many adult animals with curable health problems (some serious, including Heartworm positive dogs) are restored to health and offered for adoption.

We take pregnant and nursing moms with their babies.
• We find foster homes for them to raise their young in a safe environment. Pounds put these moms and their babies down immediately because of the risk of illness, extra work and additional space involved with caring for them.

We work closely with Will County and Joliet Township Animal Control to help reduce the kill rate of animals locally.

We sponsor an Illinois Dept of Agriculture Humane Investigator, who serves our geographic area and investigates cruelty complaints.

We offer training and behavioral counseling to assist in the transition of adopted animals into new homes.

Go Meet Their Pets

animal.description:
Before you inquire about Zarah, please read her bio as she will require a person who has the experience and knowledge working with strong willed large breeds. Only local inquiries (within 30 miles of Sacramento/Roseville) will be considered as she will require multiple meets before adoption. No cats, no apartments.

Zarah is a beautiful Doberman/Malinois mix, about 6 1/2 months old (DOB ~7/3/20) and currently weighs 58 lbs. She loves very much to be with her person, but that person needs to understand that she needs structure and boundaries.  She needs an experienced person who is consistent, calm and assertive.  She walks great on a leash, loves to go for walks and is good in the car. She needs a person with an active lifestyle, someone who goes for daily walks, or likes to hike, is dedicated and has the time to continue socializing her the correct way. She is good with the dogs she currently lives with, but needs to be introduced to new dogs in the correct manner.  Once introduce correctly, she loves to play, but is definitely not a dog park dog.  She knows basic commands and is eager to learn. She is very attentive when learning new things and is very smart.  She is being introduced to new environments and has been good, but as with other introductions it needs to be done correctly.  Once she meets new people, she is is very loving. She is great in the house and is crate trained. She would do well with another well behaved mellow confident dog. A home with no children or dog savvy kids over the age of 12 will only be considered. If you have Doberman/Shepherd or other large working breed experience and are a committed owner, this dog may be for you.

Please email right away if you would like to learn more about this dog......and visit our website www.siarescuers.org to learn more about our rescue group.   Adoption fees range from $200-$400 for dogs.  THE DOGS SHOWN ON THE SITE ARE IN FOSTERCARE - WE DO NOT HAVE A SHELTER TO VISIT.  EMAIL is the best way to reach us.We are a volunteer run, very small organization - so please be patient when waiting for a response, but feel free to check back in if you haven't heard from us in a day or so - thank you so much for considering a rescued pooch!

animal.description:
Meet Rhett! 

Rhett
Say hello to Rhett, a 55lb male hound/lab mix! Rhett is the gentlest, sweetest dog you will meet this side of the Mississippi! He is both dog and cat friendly and sleeps quietly in his crate at night. Rhett’s foster family doesn’t believe he has ever lived in a home before or had a family to call his own. He has been very well behaved, but Rhett is still learning about all the new luxuries he has now such as toys, yummy treats, and ear rubs from humans. Rhett would benefit from a family who will be patient with him as he learns all the nuances of living in a home. He would really like a fenced in yard so he can roam and play in the snow and a doggie friend to play with and learn from. If you think Rhett might be your family’s perfect match, please apply to adopt at mapawsmepetrescue.com 

Interested in meeting Rhett? 

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

Our process is as follows:
1.  Review our policies and adoption radius  on our website: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/
2.  Submit an application for review and approval;
3.  MPM Rescue reviews application and checks vet records and references;
4.  MPM foster contacts approved applicant(s) to arrange a home check and meeting with available dog(s);
5.   If there is a good fit, adoption is completed with a contract and fees (payable via check or cash).

The adoption fee is listed here: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/

Dogs from Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
- Spay/Neuter surgery
- Age appropriate vaccinations
- Heartworm test (for dogs over 6mo) and treatment if positive
- Microchip
- Deworming
- Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
- Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

*Please note that the identified breed(s) are best guesses. We very rarely have information on our dogs' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays.*

animal.description:
Joey was rescued from a slaughterhouse in China and is looking for his forever home. This handsome Labrador Retriever weighs 72 lbs. and is three years old. Joey’s foster family is very proud of how quickly he’s acclimated to home life and they enjoy how curious Joey is about everything. He loves to play fetch, chew on toys, and chase a large soccer sized ball around the yard; if he finds a large rock on his walk he’ll use his nose and front paws to toss it around – this is likely something he did to entertain himself when he was in China. Joey sleeps soundly through the night in his crate and loves to have his face massaged; he’s yet to show any indication that he wants a belly rub. Joey walks very well on the leash but if he finds a rock or food/trash, he will pull towards it. Joey knows the word “treat” and his favorite time of the day is breakfast, lunch, and dinner – he arrived underweight so his foster family is working on helping him gain some much-needed pounds. Joey is working on his house manners and his foster family reports his counter surfing has diminished a great deal in a short time. Joey is a big dog, but he has a soft mouth and takes treats gently. Joey loves to go for car rides and rides very well in the car. Joey needs lots of attention, he requires a bunch of activities to stimulate his mind, an active adopter who can spend time playing with him, and someone with the patience to continue to help him adjust to being a family dog inside the house. His ideal home will also need someone who is dog savvy and committed to continuing to set him up for success by doing things like keeping all food off the kitchen counter and using positive reinforcement to teach Joey the ways of the world.

If you are interested in adopting from us, please complete an adoption application at our website (www.fetchinretrieversrescue.org). Once your application is received, it will be reviewed and you may be contacted to arrange a home visit. In keeping with our adoption process, there are no meet and greets with a dog until all steps in the application process have been completed and a potential match has been made. We adhere to this policy because we strive to ensure adoption success between dogs and their new family.

animal.description:
Graham is a very special boy. After beating mange, heartworms, and cancer, he has received a clean bill of health is ready to live the rest of his life with his furever family! He is doing great at his foster home. Although he's shown a little food and toy aggression with the other dogs,  it can likely be managed with some structure, routine and training. He's a submissive boy, does well with the adults and kids in his foster family, and walks well on leash. 

If you are interested in pursuing an adoption and you live in Texas , please complete the application (links provided below). The process includes a vet check, calling references and doing a home visit. 

http://www.texassleddogrescue.org/web_documents/tsdr_application.pdf
or
https://www.formstack.com/forms/?1632205-WX2Zb144ZP

Please note the following:
We rarely do out of state adoptions.  (Exceptions can be discussed but will be based on previous big dog experience and will require same adoption process.)
Children in the home or that visit often must be at least 6 years of age. (Exceptions can be discussed but will be based on previous big dog experience.)
Adoption donation is due at the time of adoption.  Puppies under 1 year are $300. Dogs 1 year to 7 years are $200 and dogs over 7 years are $150.  As this is a donation, it will be non-returnable if dog is returned to rescue.
Dogs are not placed on a "first come, first serve" basis but rather the best home for the dog. 
All dogs placed by TSDR will be:
spayed/neutered
vaccinated for distemper/parvo, rabies, and bordetella
heartworm tested and treated if needed
microchipped
other vetting as deemed needed
New owners will receive copies of all available vet information and must agree to keep them current on all of the above.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.If interested in any of our animals for adoption, or to foster an animal, please fill out the respective application here to get the process started. Visit our FAQ webpage for commonly asked questions about our adoption/foster process.
Buster says, "Any dog is a lap dog, as long as he sits on your lap!" He's big, but he sure does love to snuggle, and his silky soft fur will make you want to pet him all day. Buster is 8 years old which is the perfect age; he's low maintenance and happy to be lazy around the house, but also appreciates a good walk and is ready to play when you are. Buster does have some anxiety, but is easily comforted with love and treats. He will do best in a home with no small children or other pets. Buster already knows a few tricks, but he could benefit from some additional obedience training, and needs to work on his leash manners. Buster already has his own bed, harness, leash, toys, Kong's, and anything else a dog could need, so all you have to provide is a loving home!Last Day Dog Rescue now microchips all animals before adoption. Microchips are implanted between the animals shoulder blades and are a permanent form of identification. The microchips are registered to Last Day Dog Rescue with the adopter's info added once adopted. If the animal is ever lost and slips his/her collar/tags the microchip allows the finder to know who to contact if scanned for a microchip. Animals MUST still have a collar with tags on at all times. Per our contract, we take all our animals back if for any reason you can't keep your adopted animal.

Please understand the statements about this animal are based upon the foster home's evaluation of the animal. The animal might behave differently (negatively or positively) in your home. While the animal might be good with the current foster's dogs, cats, children, etc., it may not be with your animal(s) or children. The animal may be housebroken or litter trained in the home of the foster but may relapse in your home. The animal is represented to the public as it performs in the foster home and any statements made regarding the animal are conditional to that foster home setting. Please understand that statements made regarding this animal are simply overviews and are not guaranteed.

The Petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our animals. Visual breed identification in animals is unreliable so for most of the animals we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each animal as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our animals based on personality, not by breed label.

Thank you for looking through our list of animals needing forever homes and choosing rescue first. We appreciate you stopping by.

Meet the young and handsome Colby Jack!

Colby Jack is a 12-month-old male, brindle, American Staffordshire terrier mix. He is vetted, vaccinated, healthy, neutered, and ready for you to open your heart and welcome him home!

This handsome, affectionate boy was a re-home and previously lived with a family with an 11-year-old, so he's good with children and received love from the time he was a puppy. They moved from a home with a yard to an apartment and wanted better for Colby Jack.

He loves long walks, is housebroken. Colby Jack would be best in a home with a yard, as he is a big boy weighing in at approximately 60 pounds. He loves to be around his loved ones and will even chill with you on the couch if allowed.

This guy is non-reactive to other dogs, so we think he'd do well with a proper introduction. He has been through some training, as well.

So if you're looking for some fine cheese, Colby Jack is your guy! So if you'd like to meet him,

please submit a completed
adoption application found
at www.doggiebonez.com so that we can schedule a meet and greet. He is also on all of our social media pages IG: @Doggie_Bonez_Inc_ and Facebook: Doggie Bonez.

If adoption isn't an option, please consider fostering one of our pups. We are a volunteer-run non-profit dog rescue and always welcome new short or long-term doggie foster families. We much appreciate the help and time of our fosters. You provide all the love, comfort, and safety of a home, and we supply you with everything else you may need, dog food, dog bed, toys, medical attention (if required), etc. If you are interested, please visit www.doggiebonez.com to see all of our available dogs who need a foster family while waiting for their fur-ever home and complete the foster application.

animal.description:
BEAUTY IS IN A FOSTER HOME

Date of birth:  5/2019

1/7/2021: Beauty is a one year old American Staffordshire mix— and she is indeed a beauty!  She has a gorgeous black coat and soulful eyes.  She weighs 65 lbs.  

• Beauty is a real sweetheart!  She’s pretty calm and well mannered. She likes to give hugs.

• Beauty lives in a  foster home with other dogs and does well with them all.  If you have a dog we’d ask you to bring your dog in to meet Beauty to see if they could be buddies.

• She likes toys…and will take them from her doggie friends. Any dog in the home would need to be passive about her stealing their toys. 

• Beauty loves being with her foster parents. She loves napping and spending time indoors with the family much more than outdoors in the yard.

• We think Beauty would be okay with older kids.

• She’s not a big barker, but she barks enough that we think she would not be a good match for apartment or townhouse living.  She has a loud deep bark.

• She rides nicely in the car and has pretty good leash manners on walks.  

• Her foster parents say she lets them wipe her feet when they get muddy or snowy…. good to know in this wintry weather! 
 
• She is house trained and crate trained.  

• Beauty has been spayed, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for heartworms.  She was a stray.  She’s a sweetie! 

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE:  PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU.  Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info. 

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Dog Adoption Contact Info:
Email: christine@hsgkc.org
Phone: 913.521.2339
hsgkc.org

For more information contact Kelly.V@HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

DOGS are in Foster Homes. There is NO shelter.

**Our companions MUST live in your home as part of your family.**We do not transport.

**See our website for more information. www.HeidisLegacyDogRescue.com

All communication is thru email so please be patient with us. We are all volunteers and work full time jobs and have families of our own.

It takes anywhere between 3-7 days to process an application - the more complete the application the easier it is for us to process it. Please notify your vet that we will be contacting them and to release information to us.

ADOPTION PROCESS:

1. Complete this application
www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/apply-to-foster-or-adopt

***Everyone must submit an application - we only keep them on file for 1 month

2. Application background check, vet check, etc

3. Invitation thru email to meet the dog(s).

4. Adoption Contract

Hi. My name is McKee. I am a 9 year old Miniature Poodle. My adoption fee is $350, Houston area
(Available for transport $550, includes adoption fee, health certificate, and transportation)
. I am neutered, microchipped, and tested heartworm negative. Fill out an app at www.soca-fbc.org under the adoptable tab.

McKee is a sweet boy who is more of a lapdog than not. He is shy. I haven't seen him play with toys, and he has only initiated playing chase once with the resident dogs. He would probably do best being an only dog or with older dogs such as himself. He doesn't like aggressive dogs getting in his face as he will snap at them. I think he would do best in a home with only adults and/or older considerate kids. He likes to curl up on the couch on a blanket by himself. He is not housebroken but is working on it. He is able and willing to jump up on furniture including beds and the kitchen table. He has been an outside dog so being in a home and being treated as a family member is new to him. He needs to taught manners by an understanding adult in a gentle manner. He needs to be in a quiet spot to eat as he is distracted easily. He loves human attention. He likes to sleep in bed with his humans. He is so tiny, just 9 lbs. so appears to be younger than his 9 years. Could your open your heart and home to this sweet boy?

OUR ADOPTION PROCESS AND APPLICATION ARE AVAILABLE AT WWW.SOHODOGRESCUE.ORG AND OUR ADOPTION FEE IS $275

Comet is a fun, happy Australian Shepherd mix who is ready for his forever home.  He is about a year old, weighs 45 pounds, and has a shorthaired blue merle coat and full tail.  This smart guy is housebroken, crate-trained and he knows his basic obedience commands.  Comet is very good on leash and absolutely loves to go for rides in the car.
Comet is reserved when he first meets new people, but once he gets to know you he is your high-Velcro best friend.  Comet loves to be with people, and he loves playing ball, Frisbee and tug.  He also loves other dogs – he is playful and even silly with them!  Chase is his favorite game with other dogs.  He is an active, fun-loving guy, but he does have a slight hip dysplasia, and if he plays hard you will see a slight limp in his right rear leg.  The vets who have examined Comet say that no treatment is required other than some joint supplements, and he even though he will play ball 24/7 if he could, he is a dog who should be limited to normal, backyard ball games – no serious competitive sports for him.  Comet is cat-friendly, and he even gives them a play-bow to try and get them to play with him!
The ideal home for Comet is full of fun, topped with a healthy serving of love!  He is all about love, play, and being part of the family 24/7.  A fenced yard is important and another playful dog or two would be perfect.  Children 10 and over, and cats, are welcome!  Comet is such a happy guy and he will bring such joy to his new family, maybe yours?  Apply today!  Comet is fostered in Kingsport, TN.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Winston and I LOVE to smile. As a matter of fact, I'm pretty sure I don't know how to stop smiling. Even when I was in that scary, crowded Texas shelter, I was always putting my best face forward in hopes someone would notice me. Boy, was I lucky when the people at Dolly's Legacy saw me and chose me to come to their rescue! That REALLY gave me a reason to smile! Some interesting facts about me....would you believe I was born with an all black coat? Yep, it's true. I used to be a black dog. Now I'm this combination of gold & white, which just makes me look like a white dog who got dipped into a pot of gold. I have a condition called vitiligo which causes my skin to lose it's pigment. Don't worry, it doesn't hurt and I don't even notice until I look in the mirror (gosh, I am handsome!).  Another thing about me, I love to run & play so I really want a big yard where I can be off leash and frolic to my heart's content. I spent way too long cooped up in a shelter so I'm all about relishing in the moment now with my newfound freedom. Sometimes I'm picky about which dogs I want to be my friends, and I most certainly don't want to make friends with any cats. They have scary claws, so I will take a hard pass on living with one of those creatures. I'm a BIG guy, packing a hefty 95 lbs, and I play hard, so little kids probably aren't the best idea even though I love them. I don't want to knock them down in my zest for fun & games. I was a long-termer at the shelter, but the staff loved me so much, they refused to send me to a rainbow bridge and instead kept me until rescue found me. I'm super happy about that, because I love every minute of being a rescue dog! Winston is a Lab/mix, weighs 95 lbs and was born approximately 10-28-14. He is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, tested negative for heartworm disease. Adoption fee is $375 to help offset the many expenses we have for vetting costs. We rely strictly on adoption fees and donations to continue to save the lives of orphaned & abandoned pets; 100% goes towards their care. If interested in adopting one of our available dogs or puppies, please complete an online adoption application at https://dollyslegacyanimalrescue.org/adopt/ You will be contacted by our adoption coordinator via email after your application has been reviewed & approved to schedule an appointment.
