animal.description:
We are pleased to introduce Zeke to the IPR Family. He joined us on Christmas Day, the day before his six-month old birthday. Zeke is a big boy, full of energy and typical puppy behavior, but very easy to redirect. For a young pup, he is well-behaved and listens pretty well. Zeke is potty trained, will let you know when he needs to go out, is crate trained, does well over night as well as for a few hours at a time during the day. He knows basic commands such as sit, shake and down. Zeke is getting close to perfecting rolling over. He enjoys walks and is pretty hilarious watching because he has this very cute prance when he walks. Zeke interacts and plays well with the foster resident dog. He might be a little too exciteable for smaller children because he is so playful, but definitely with supervision and training will be able to overcome that.  

Get your apps in for Zeke at rescueapittie.org

animal.description:
Hey everybody it's Rebel here. I am a 2 year old male retriever lab mix. I tested positive for heart-worm, but I have had all my treatments and medications done I just have one more shot on the 13th then after that I will just need heart guard once a month for the rest of my life. Besides having heart-worm I am a healthy happy guy who is looking for a furrever home.
I am a very energetic excitable guy who loves to play and go for walks. I do tend to mark my territory a lot so I would need some training to stop doing that.
I was walked through the cat room here at the shelter and it is not 100% for sure because there is a glass door between us, but I did not mind the cats so if you have cats in the home that is fine with me.
I am picky on other dogs so please make sure to bring any other dog you have in the home to come meet with me to make sure we would get along.
I get along with children so any kiddos in the home to play with is okay with me.
My adoption fee is $185 with a qualified application.
If you'd like to put an application in for me you can do so at the shelter website Stephenmemorial.org and once it has been qualified you will get a call to set up an appointment to meet with me.

animal.description:
Olive is a 1-2 year, 29lb small mixed breed. We think there might be some lab, beagle and terrier in there! Olive LOVES to snuggle with her humans and is especially taken with her 7 year old 'sister.' She enjoys snuggling on couches, beds, chairs, ANYWHERE! She appears to be medium-high velcro and forms a quick attachment to her humans. She is very sweet and loves to give and receive affection.

Olive can be very high-energy and loves to play with her foster family's other dog. They both love to roll around, chase each other, and run in the yard. Olive is learning how to walk on a leash and is showing interest in playing fetch. She is a more dominate dog and tends to boss the other dog around from time to time.

Olive is not completely housebroken yet but she is close! She does well at night and is able to sleep through the night in a crate without any accidents.

Olive is nervous in new situations and would do best with another dog in her home to give her confidence and a family that provides structure. Once she is comfortable in a new place, she happily gives kisses and tail wags. Olive needs a home with a yard and a family that is patient as she gets her bearings in a new place. She is spayed, up to date on vaccines and eager to find a family to love! 

The adoption fee for this dog is $350 which includes routine vetting and spay/neuter. 

For more information, please contact khasse@petconnectrescue.org

**If you're viewing this on Petfinder, please visit www.petconnectrescue.org to complete our non-binding application.**

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Barney! I'm estimated to be a Hound mix born around 4/9/2019. I came up to Wisconsin from Texas and weigh close to 54 pounds. I was adopted as a puppy and brought back because I was becoming aggressive with the other dog in the home.  I am a dog that will do best with positive reinforcement training as I have bitten people before when spoken to and stared at harshly.  Since coming back to the shelter, I have loved everyone here.  I was great with the vet and I have wonderful manners.  I keep my kennel clean and make human friends easily.  I have the capability of being a wonderful dog but I do react when I feel threatened.  Obedience classes for adult dogs and puppies can be incredibly helpful for both animals and humans. It helps you understand what makes me tick and will give me a better idea of what you want me to do. It’s a win/win and it will also strengthen the bond between us! Apply for me today!

My adoption fee is $60.00. Adoption applications can be filled out at CCHS or online through our website, www.cchs-petshelter.org. Applications are not first come, first served. All applications will be reviewed by the adoption committee and the home chosen will be the one considered to be the best match. All dogs and puppies have been vaccinated for Distemper and Bordetella, dewormed and microchipped. If old enough, they will be vaccinated for Rabies and blood tested for Heartworm, Lymes, Anaplasmosis and Erlichiosis. Dogs and puppies will be spayed or neutered before adoption.

CCHS is proud to be a No-Kill Humane Society. As a private, non-profit charity, our work depends on donations and volunteers to keep going. We are committed to helping the animals that enter our doors and finding each the best possible forever home. CCHS has been inspected and licensed by the Department of Animal Health - DATCP. Our license is #268235-DS

animal.description:
If you are interested in any of the dogs available at New Leash Rescue, you can reach out to the foster listed below for more information and then complete an adoption application which can be found at https://www.newleashrescue.org/adopt/policy.  Please email the completed application to newleashrescue2018@gmail.com

**Adoptable only as a pair with Harley**

Riggs is estimated to be around two and a half years old old.  He is estimated to be a Cane Corso mix.  He was found with Harley, completely emaciated, after being dumped from someone's vehicle in a park.    A good samaritan saw this happen, and helped to get both dogs to safety.      When Riggs was found, he weighted less than 60 pounds, but has been able to put on weight and looks much better.  

Riggs is good with other dogs, as long as there isn't food involved.  He will growl too if he thinks another dog is trying to take it away, so he is used to being fed in a kennel.    If another dog in the household has food that they are eating, they needs to be in a kennel until they are done.     If you were starved like they were, you can't blame them for feeling like they need to protect their food.  Hopefully this will go away in time with consistency of food and a stable environment, but kennel feeding may be needed long term.   Riggs has not shown any protectiveness around items with his foster mom. 

Riggs is the shy guy and was very scared at first.  He stayed mostly to his kennel or venturing a small area around.  He is very unsure of slippery floors and wood steps.  It has taken him quite awhile to come around to using the stairs to go outside in his foster home.  At first he was using some potty pads, but is now going outside to do his business since he's more comfortable.   Riggs is going to need patience and understanding, and a refresher on house training in a new home.    

He is currently living with a fenced yard.  If other dogs are in the home, Riggs will do best with females, and submissive males.    
Due to the resource protection, we do not want to place Harley or Riggs in a home with young kids. Kids recommended age 10 and up.   They also need to have a fenced in yard.  They have not been cat tested. 

Harley has a wonderful connection to Riggs.  They will lay together, and she will lick and clean him.   We want them to stay together.  


Adoption fee is $600/pair + tax (no checks)

Foster to contact: Katie  @ kit_n_caboodle22@hotmail.com


Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. 

Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

animal.description:
Mylie ? 
This sweet lady joined our group when her incontinence was a little too much to handle with the new baby in the house. She is a beautiful 3 year old purebred lab. Unfortunately she has some incontinence issues and is on 2 medications for life for this. The cost is around $100 per month. She does not need to be one any special food though. 
Here is a little about her from her foster family:
Very affectionate - loves belly rubs and snuggles, she’ll even crawl under the blankets if you let her in the bed. She gets along great with other dogs but does not like to share toys, not aggressive just doesn’t like to share. LOVES tennis balls and any toy that squeaks. She’ll play fetch all day long, will destroy/rip apart plus/stuffed toys as well as tennis balls.  Enjoys water and can dock jump. She’s attentive to guns and doesn’t seem afraid (unsure if she will hunt or not). Knows how to use doggy door - we feel that this has really helped her and would be a big plus for a future home.
 Is trained on open bowl feeding. 
Unsure of how she would be with children.
Pretty good with taking her pills - she likes peanut butter. Fairly obedient. Knows sit, stay, here, heal, lay down, and roll over.
We believe she would be best with an active family. She has an endless amount of energy and needs the opportunity to be active. Any situation where she could go outside at her leisure would be best to help with her urinary incontinence.
Adoption fee $300
Adoption Applications available at rpaw.org

animal.description:
Curtis is about two-years old, around 60 lbs. He was a stray that showed up at a families home and he could have stayed but was stealing all the neighbor's packages. He is a very loving dog, wants to be a big lap dog. He is quite striking in appearance, good with dogs and cats. His special need is that he has tested positive for heartworms and starts his treatment on 20 Jan so will be available for adoption by the end of February. KEEP YOUR DOGS ON HEARTWORM PREVENTION PLEASE!

ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00 . This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html
IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

animal.description:
If you are interested in any of the dogs available at New Leash Rescue, you can reach out to the foster listed below for more information and then complete an adoption application which can be found at https://www.newleashrescue.org/adopt/policy.  Please email the completed application to newleashrescue2018@gmail.com

**Adoptable as a pair with Riggs**

Harley is estimated to be around a year and a half old.  She is maybe a Cane Corso/Pitbull mix.  She was found with another male dog, completely emaciated, after being dumped from someone's vehicle in a park.    A good samaritan saw this happen, and helped to get both dogs to safety.      When Harley was found, she weighed well under 40 pounds.  Now she is up to almost 45# currently.  

Harley is good with other dogs, as long as there isn't food involved.  She likes to chew on nylabones and will growl too if she thinks another dog is trying to take it away from her.   If another dog in the household has food that they are eating, Harley needs to be in a kennel until they are done.  

She is fine with her foster mom taking things away.   If you were starved like her, you can't blame her for feeling like she needs to protect things.   As she has gotten more comfortable, she will even romp, play, and chase with other dogs outside.   

She was very shy at first but was the first to warm up and venture around and learn the stairs.   At first she was using some potty pads, but is now going outside to do her business since she's more comfortable.    She is currently living with a fenced in yard.     Harley will be very shy and scared in new situations and will need time to warm up.   

Due to the resource protection, we do not want to place Harley or Riggs in a home with young kids. Kids recommended age 10 and up.   They also need to have a fenced in yard.  They have not been cat tested. 

Harley has a wonderful connection to Riggs.  They will lay together, and she will lick and clean him.   We want them to stay together.  


Adoption fee is $600/pair + tax (no checks)

Foster to contact: Katie  @ kit_n_caboodle22@hotmail.com

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. 

Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

animal.description:
Dorothy is ten years old and about 45 lbs. She was abandoned in pitiful condition and her foster mom has worked diligently bringing her back to health. She is simply a wonderful gal that loves everyone and everything. She does have some significant special needs though as she has Cushings but is doing very well on her Vetoryl meds. AND she has heartworms but has started Advantage Multi instead of a full immiticide treatment (talk to your Vet if this is not familiar to you). She is housetrained, walks wonderfully on a leash, is great with other dogs of all sizes and both sexes, is good with cats. She eats in her crate but prefers sleeping in the bed with her human. She is perfect in the house. Now FYI - Dorothy drinks a LOT of water, a LOT. This is the Cushings but she does not need to 'go' all of the time and has stayed inside for four hour stretches with no problem. But more than that would likely not be good for her and what we really want for her is a home with someone at home most of the time so she is never parked in a back yard. This girl is worth it and she deserves of a soft bed and lots of love for the rest of her life with some play time & nice long walks. Dorothy is a very special lady indeed!
This is from Dorothy's foster mom:
Dorothy is the easiest foster dog I have ever had. What a sweet girl, good with my cats, dogs and all the people she meets. I haven't seen her around children but I can't imagine that would be a problem, nothing reactive or snappy about this girl. She is quiet and very good in the house, but has plenty of energy to play when we go outside. She loves walks and walks well on a leash, perfectly fine with riding in the car. She barks once to let me know she needs to go out and again to let me know it's time to come in so she is also a good communicator! Please consider adding Dorothy, a very special senior dog, to your family.

ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00 . This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.

The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html

IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

animal.description:
'L' Litter 2020Updated: 1/6/2021
Litter Name: 'L' Litter 2020 (mom)
Roxie is pure joy. She is about 3 years old and weighs about 30 lbs. She gets along with other dogs and cats and loves to snuggle! She loves going on walks and she LOVES a treat now and again. She enjoys just hanging out on the couch too. She is completely house trained, has a wonderfully sweet disposition and has been great to have around. She is good with children too.
Adoption Fee: $475.00
We are a Wisconsin state licensed dog rescue -WI# 402433

***We do not have a central adoption center at this time. All our dogs are in private foster homes within WI. At this time we only place our dogs in areas of WI. The breed of our dogs is our best guess with the help of our veterinarians.
Our Weight Classes are as follows:
0- 25lbs - Small
26- 45lbs - Medium
46-89 - Large
90+ X-large
If you are adopting an adult dog, which we consider 6 months of age or older, your adoption fee includes the following:
Spay/Neuter, Rabies and Distemper shots, dewormed, flea & tick preventative, heartworm tested and microchipped.
If you are adopting a dog younger than 6 months of age, the dog will be up to date on the shots as per the dogs age. The dog will be dewormed, flea/tick preventative and microchipped. We only spay/neuter our dogs by 6 months of age. If you decide to adopt a younger dog than 6 months of age, they will need to be spayed/neutered at one of our preferred clinics. This will be determined by your contract along with the month they should have their surgery. This is included in your adoption fee.
Once you are approved with our rescue, you can meet any one of our dogs within the fosters home. If you are interested in the dog you met, you can take the dog home under our mandatory foster to adopt program. You receive 5 days to see if the dog is the right fit for your home.
If it is, we will conduct the home visit and finalize adoption. If it is not, it is returned to the foster. We are happy to find you another dog that meets your needs in your home.
If a dog is listed as PENDING, a family has met the dog and planning on adopting the dog after the home visit has been conducted. We always suggest sending in an application for a dog because there are times where the dogs are given back to us under the foster to adopt program. There are many reasons dogs are returned but normally it just was not the right fit for all.Please go to WWW.TAILWAGGERS911.COM under HOW TO ADOPT . We have an online application that is very easy to fill out. 2/2/21 5:21 PM

animal.description:
Hi my name is Cinch and I’m about 5 months old. I’m listed as a bird dog mix and a little over 20 lbs (I definitely need to gain some weight). I was a stray so I’m continuing to learn to be in a home. My foster mom says I’m a quick learner but I’m definitely a typical puppy. I’m still working on potty training. When my foster mom is home we go outside every two hours or so and that way I don’t potty in the house. I’m not a huge fan of how the snow makes my feet cold but I know to do my business right away. I’m awesome in my crate. If you give me a few toys and some treats, I don’t make a peep and I sleep through the night no problems. I even do great in the crate when my foster mom is at work. I love romping around with the resident dogs who are a lot bigger than me. I rarely bark unless I’m trying to get the dogs to play with me. I don’t understand why they bark at the window. I also met the cat, I’m not quite sure about her, she kind of scares me so I just leave her be. I like to check on her now and again but she won’t play with me. I love toys but I love nylabones (or any other durable toy) the best! When I get tired, I love to snuggle up with my foster mom. Laps are my favorite!
 
I’m still working on some things.  I eat my food way too fast. But I’m doing great using a slow feeder. I still need to work on taking treats gently. I can take training treats gently, but I’m too excited to get high value treats that I forget I’m supposed to be gentle. They are just so good I can’t help myself. I also get so excited when playing and giving kisses that sometimes I forget that I’m not supposed to use my teeth.

If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for one of our great dogs, please go to our website- www.luckymuttsrescue.org and submit an application. Our application process includes landlord approval and vet checks. Please make sure all of your information is current and accurate, including a valid email address and phone numbers. Inaccuracies and/or incomplete data will delay and/or cancel your application.  We strive to process all applications in a timely manner, but with the high volume of applications we are receiving, it is taking anywhere from 1-3 weeks.  You may be contacted via email if there are concerns or questions.  Once all of your information is reviewed and if your application is approved, you will be notified via email.  Submitting an application and receiving an approval does not guarantee you will be adopting the dog you applied for.  Once you move to the meet and greet process, you will be contacted by the foster family to further discuss the dog, and answer questions you may have, and if applicable, a meet and greet will be set up at our adoption center.   Meet and greets are only set up with approved applicants, and we require all members in the household to be present, as well as any current dogs in the home. 

Current Adoption Fees Are:
$400+tax for puppies to 3 years old
$350+tax for ages 4-7
$250+tax for ages 8 and up
Bonded pairs vary

The adoption fee covers spay/neuter, up to date age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, general deworming, heartworm test, (if over 6  months) and a certified veterinary inspection. Please be aware, listed dog breeds are based on information provided and cannot be guaranteed.  Submitting an application for a particular dog does not guarantee that you will be the applicant chosen, we receive several applications for each dog. Our adopters are picked based on the needs of the dog, and the home we feel with best fit based on your responses to our application, vet information and landlord requirements.   Approved applicants not chosen for the dog you applied for, will be in active status for a period of six months.  We encourage you to watch Petfinder, Facebook and our website for upcoming dogs.  Should you see a dog that interests you, please send us a Facebook message or an email with your approval number.  Please be patient with us, as Lucky Mutts Rescue is run strictly by volunteers and many of us work full time jobs, have families and also foster dogs. Thank you for considering Lucky Mutts Rescue for your next furry family member!

animal.description:
Summer is an approximately  2.5 year old, famle, hound mix who is looking for her forever family. She was a loving, attentive momma who is now ready for her chance to find a home of her own. Summer is full of sunshine and warmth! She is very affectionate and is an incredibly sweet and gentle girl.Don’t let her size fool you, this lady is super friendly and will just melt into you! Summer is looking for a family that will spoil her like she deserves.

Summer and Sunshine, these remarkable sisters, were rescued by STARS when they were found wandering the roads in the backcountry of Georgia. Summer was named after the country town where she was found, abandoned and wandering the streets. It was very clear that Summer was extremely pregnant and under fed. She was happy to find a safe, warm, loving environment with STARS  to give. She gave birth to 8 beautiful, healthy puppies shortly after. Now that both of these sisters puppies have been adopted,Summer is ready to make her debut! Summer has regained her strength with lots of love in the process, and is finally ready to find her furever home. Summer deserves the world and we know that we will be able to find a family that can give that to her.

Click on www.starsrescue.org to complete an application to be pre-approved to adopt this pup. As you can imagine, we get a lot of interest in our rescues and kindly ask that you are patient with us while we review applications as it may take a  few days.We will contact you regarding your application, during which you can ask more questions about this specific pup. If pre-approved we will coordinate a date for meet and greet.

Our adoption fee is $500. This includes spay/neuter, microchipping, deworming, and all age-appropriate vaccinations.

animal.description:
Hello everyone my name is Felix the shepherd mix now known as Roxy in my foster home. Funny story actually I came to Wisconsin making everyone believe I was a  boy but I’m actually a girl! I love love love to play in the snow and just lick the snow away all day. I’ve also been told I listen very well. I go potty outside and sit when I’m told especially if there’s a T-R-E-A-T involved. My least favorite thing to do is go in my crate but I only cry sometimes when I have to go in it. I’m still not sure what this leash thing their talking about really is but my foster mom says I’m adjusting nicely to it. All in all I love to play outside or take a nice long nap on the couch. I’m pretty go with the flow and love all my resident dog siblings. At 6 months I’m a very smart girl who loves to please my humans.

animal.description:
You are my sunshine, my only sunshine. You make me happy when skies are grey.

Sunshine is surely going to brighten your day! Sunshine is an approximately  2.5year old, famle, hound mix who is looking for her forever family. She is very sweet with a calm demeanor. Sunshine is very loving, affectionate, and looking for a family to provide warmth to this winter! She truly has a heart of gold. With Sunshine around, your days will always be bright!

Summer and Sunshine, these remarkable sisters, were rescued by STARS when they were found wandering the roads in the backcountry of Georgia. It was very clear that Summer was extremely pregnant and under fed. She was happy to find a place to give birth to her young. But this story isn’t about Summer, her sister Sunshine needed a bit more coaxing. It took several weeks for STARS founder Willene to gain Sunshine’s  trust and eventually perseverance won and Sunshine was rescued.  Little did we know Sunshine was also newly pregnant and was just using her mother instinct to make sure STARS was safe. Sunshine gave birth to three cuddly puppies on March 21, 2020. After a few months of regaining her strength with lots of love in the process, Sunshine is finally ready to find her furever home. Sunshine deserves the world and we know that we will be able to find a family that can give that to her.

animal.description:
Meet Ellie! This sweet senior is looking for her furever family and home!

Ellie is estimated to be between 8-10 years old and she has been through a lot in those years. Shortly after being found about 2 months ago in rural Virginia (abandoned, emaciated, and tied to a tree

), she was diagnosed with diabetes. Her diabetes had been left untreated for so long that she developed cataracts, making her mostly blind. There is also evidence that she was shot at some point in her life

.

Despite everything humans have put her through, Ellie is very outgoing and loves nothing more than snuggling up and meeting new people! She moves around well using her nose

and ears

. She did well with 2 dogs that are laid back like she is, but she's not fond of cats.

Ellie is spayed, microchipped, up to date on vaccinations, and house trained. Please consider opening your heart and home to this loving, sweet, deserving girl!

Our best guess is she is a min pin mix. She currently weighs about 20 lbs. and is slowly putting weight back on now that we seem to have gotten her diabetes under control, and still need to gain a few lbs. as you can see from her after pic.

To be considered to adopt Ellie, please submit our Dog/Puppy Adoption Application as this is the FIRST step in our process: https://form.jotform.com/203643479832159

NOTE: we are a foster-based rescue in Southeastern Pennsylvania which means we don't have a physical location (our sanctuary is for our farm animals only). We only set up meets for approved applicants and you must be located within 2 hours of Philadelphia.

animal.description:
Name: Albert
Nicknames: Alb. Albs.
Breed: Spaniel/Pointer/Hound Mix
Age: ~ 1 Year
Weight: 23 lbs.
Before OMD: Albert and 15 other dogs were rescued from a horrific hoarding situation by one of our partner rescues when they were notified that the dogs were alone, starving, and living outside in filth and squalor. Despite knowing the conditions and one of the dogs being found deceased on a mound of trash, local officials said to "let nature take its course." Obviously, that wasn't an option for our partner rescue and OMD stepped up for Albert and three of his siblings.
Energy Level: Medium. Happy to cuddle and chill on the couch but also loves to run around outside like a wild man when the opportunity presents itself.
His Role Model: Scaredy Squirrel (totally worth a Google search)
Fight or flight? Flight. He's a lover not a fighter and not a fan of any type of confrontation. He is extremely shy when meeting new people, but if it’s done in a quiet place with some treats, he comes around.
Toy rating: 10/10. So awesome. Best invention ever. Highly recommended. Optimal for throwing around, chasing, carrying multiple in mouth, showing them off, and hoarding.
His other favorite things: Dog friends. Melting into the couch. 
What we love about him: His kind, loving and gentle temperament. How his confidence level increases he's carrying one of his prized possessions in his mouth. His passion for collecting things...toys, shoes, articles of clothing, thingamabobs...it's all very Arielle-esque, really. How special he makes you feel when you gain his trust and he cozies up to you for cuddles. 
Foodie Status: Big foodie! If the coast is clear and things are quiet, he’ll even accept snacks from strangers!
Selfish or happy to share: He’ll share anything. A good snoozle spot, his toys, his food, his treats.
2021 New Year’s Resolution: Gain a bit more confidence and a forever family!
Kids: Kiddos 10+ are ideal for this guy. He's afraid of his own shadow so a Brady Bunch style home will give him a heart attack. 
Dogs: Mandatory. Albert perks up immediately when there is another pup around and he looks to them for cues when scoping out new situations. We will not accept applications that do not have other dogs in the home.
Cats: Sure. Currently fostered with them. May bark initially (um, cats can be scary at first), but then settles in just fine. 
Commands: Well, nothing...yet. He’s a blank slate and ready to learn!
Housetrained: Working on it and doing well with a consistent schedule.
Crate trained: Yep! Has been a great potty training tool and he is happy to sleep in his crate through the night.
Emotional Cliff Notes: Albert needs a family that will give him time and patience so he can bloom into the wonderful family dog he is on the inside. Slow and steady will win the race (and his love).
Albert is neutered, vaccinated, heartworm negative and microchipped. He’s available to residents of CT and surrounding states. If you are interested in adopting, please complete an application from omdrescue.org.

animal.description:
Wanted: Best Friend  
Reward: Kisses, snuggles and companionship
 
Meet Pacho, a 3-year-old 96-pound mixed breed sweetheart who would love nothing more than to break your lap and lavish you with love.  
 
Handsome Pacho is craving a human companion. While he is fine with dogs, coexisting with them peacefully, he really just wants a human to hang out with. In return, Pacho promises to be a very good boy. He is housebroken and sleeps well in his crate overnight. He’s not a barker or a chewer, unless it’s his own toys. And he’s really smart; Pacho knows sit, down, come, drop, and no, and could easily be taught more commands. Pacho can sometimes be protective of his people but otherwise shows no signs of aggression. 
 
This sweet boy just wants someone to love on. He likes to play fetch and play with his toys, but would prefer not to hang out outside unless his people are with him. Pacho is ready to show you just how much love he has to give...are you ready to accept it and give Pacho a loving home?

Interested in adopting this dog? Visit our website (http://www.SecondCityCanineRescue.org) to fill out an application and to find out where this dog may be shown this weekend.

We love our dogs. We want happy lives for all of them and are looking for the home that provides the best fit for each dog’s individual needs. Please understand that there may be multiple families interested in this dog. Come to the show to find out if this dog is the right fit for you — it's helpful to bring all family members and current dogs. 

Also, please know that the breed mix listed is simply a guess. In most cases, we don’t know their background. We encourage you to base your decision on individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on our guess.

Please understand, we only adopt our animals out near the Chicagoland area. Questions? Email us at adoptions@sccrescue.org. Hope to see you become part of the SCCR family!

animal.description:
Lexi is a sweet spoiled girl that has come  a long way since coming into rescue.  She was nearly starved to death when we received her but no fault to her owners after extensive testing we discovered that Lexi had a condition called EPI this requires her to eat ONLY a specific prescription food and have digestive supplements put on her food before eating.   She CANNOT have any other food or treats.  Currently she is doing great and has put on the weight she requires and very content.  She will however need to be monitored by a vet to make sure all is ok.  We do recommend a fenced in yard but we also need someone who will not leave her alone in a yard(for fear of eating something she is not suppose to).  Although she requires special treatment she will repay it in lots of snuggles and love.   we are attaching a link about her condition.  Ideally we would love to find someone who has dealt with EPI or currently has a dog with the condition.   If you have any questions or would like information about Lexi please email
pifanimal@yahoo.com

 https://wagwalking.com/condition/exocrine-pancreatic-insufficiency

animal.description:
Blair is an adorable two month old puppy that will be arriving to AHR on January 30th, from our shelter partner in Louisiana.

She is a little shy at first and a mama’s girl, but once she’s out of her shell very playful, pretty independent and will play with toys on her own, loves to play with other dogs, cuddle bug when it's time to chill out

Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

FOR PUPPIES: PLEASE READ!!
Homes considering Puppies must be prepared for:
Flexible Schedules for Potty Training. Puppies can only hold urine for one hour per month of age. Crate Training for the next 10 months to keep them safe from chewing on everything in your home. Supervision with Children and Obedience training. 
Socialization; both with new people, children and other dogs outside of the home.
Homes that want a well behaved dog, must be prepared to put the time, effort and costs associated to train a puppy. Well behaved dogs are not born, they are trained!  Please do not apply for a puppy if you cannot or do not have the time for a puppy.

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

Update on Enzo! His surgery was successful and he is no longer in pain and the upward spinal growth has been stopped. That was the goal of the surgery. He is running and playing like a 6 month old pup should. He is posturing to urinate, but the continence is not consistent. He wears a diaper, but that does not stop him from providing joy to the people around him. We are looking for a person or family that will commit a lifetime of love, care and support for Enzo.  adopt@thisisthedog.org

Enzo was rescued from the Miami Dade Animal Services shelter. He was an owner surrender.  We do not know how his injury happened, but we wanted to give this little guy a chance at life.  We have provided the surgery and TLC to get him ready for a new life!  Are you ready to provide a lifetime commitment?

Don't let the diapers get you down.  Enzo doesn't! He lives every day to the fullest.  He gives and gives until your face hurts from laughing and smiling.

If you are serious about giving ENZO a lifetime of the love and care that he deserves, we would love to hear from you!

Donations help us to continue rescuing dogs and cats and helping to make sure that they are healthy and properly socialized before being adopted.Thank you for considering a rescued dog/cat from This Is The Dog!. To donate www.thisisthedog.org
Follow us on Facebook www.facebook.com/thisisthedog 

ADOPTION PROCESS:
1. Email adopt@thisisthedog.org for an application.  Complete Adoption Application and return to us at adopt@thisisthedog.org or fax to 305-247-9127

2. Meet with the dog or cat. Bring treats/toys if you would like.
During COVID and for TRANSPORT- Virtual Home Visit using Facetime

3. If adoption is approved - Complete Adoption Contract

Adoption Donation - $85 for cats and $200 for dogs.

Out of state cat adoptions are $150 Two for $200
Out of state dog adoptions $300


All donations are tax deductible.

Adoption donation for dogs includes Spay/Neuter, Up to Date Vaccines, Microchip,  Deworming, and Heartworm Check if needed.  
Adoption donation for cats/kittens includes Spay/Neuter, Up to Date Vaccines, Deworming, FeLV/FIV testing and Microchip

5. Thank you! This is the Dog! does not have a shelter. Our dogs and cats are in foster homes primarily in Homestead, FL. We are a small group of volunteers making a difference in the lives of people and the dogs/cats that we help. 

TOUCH a SOUL.  CHANGE a LIFE.  PERHAPS your OWN.

FREE spay/neuter email adopt@thisisthedog.org


This is the Dog! (TITD!) makes no representation, warranty or guarantee about an animal’s breed, temperament or behavior. We also make no representation, warranty, or guarantee as to the size at maturity, health or disposition of any dog because This is the Dog!  is sometimes uncertain of an animal's background or history.  Adopter also understands that the dog has displayed no evidence of illness or health problems during its stay with TITD!, unless indicated on the medical history form.

animal.description:
Female, ~4 years old, 70 lbs.Approximate Age: ~4 years old

Approximate Weight/Size: 70 lbs.

I am an UNDERDOG because....

I am a hound mix! Hound breeds are very prominent in the rural south and usually the first to be euthanized at the shelter due to the overpopulation of this breed.

Good with: Dogs, Kids, Cats

Winnie is the sweetest dog you will ever meet. She is so curious and kind and she greets everyone, human and dog alike, with a tail wag and a kiss. She does not bark, isn't high energy, doesn't chew, and isn't aggressive. She loves treats and is shy and sweet. She loves her crate and it's her safe place -- she sleeps in her crate with the door open every night. She does not like loud noises but will be assured quickly by her human companion and she's a great listener. She loves children. She is leash reactive so she needs a home outside of the city with a fenced in yard. She also is very overweight, so she's looking for a family who can help her shed a few lbs! She is just the best dog and can't wait to find her new forever home!

Adoption Application: http://bit.ly/adoptrdr
Adoption Application:
http://bit.ly/adoptrdr

Foster Application: http://bit.ly/fosterapprdr

Adoption Process: In order to adopt, we require an adoption application. After you submit an application, if you pass the screening, we will contact you to schedule a phone interview. We will call your references, including your veterinarian and landlord (when appropriate). We will also conduct a home visit. After these steps are complete, you will be approved to adopt a dog. Please note this process takes 1-2 weeks so applications submitted when you are ready to bring a dog home within that time frame. You can meet our adoptable dogs at events, however, we cannot guarantee that dogs at events do not have pre-approved applicants meeting them there as well, so the application is the best way to start the process.

Mission Statement: Forever true to "The Underdog", Rural Dog Rescue is dedicated to saving the lives of dogs in shelters who are often overlooked for adoption or rescue. We save the dogs who are at most risk of being euthanized: the hounds, the black dogs, the seniors, the sick and the broken. We make a commitment to reserve a minimum of 50% of the dogs we save to The Underdog. Root For The Underdog!

Rural Dog Rescue's home base is in Washington, DC. We adopt to the Washington, DC metropolitan area to include Maryland and Northern Virginia.

We support several high kill shelters that euthanize in 72 hours and whose kill rate is 70% or higher in rural areas of Virginia, West Virginia, North and South Carolina. Rural Dog Rescue also helps dogs in need in Washington, DC and Maryland.

We are 100% volunteer and foster based and no salaries are paid. 100% of your donation and adoption fee goes to helping the dogs and cats of Rural Dog Rescue.

Although we try to be as accurate as possible, Rural Dog Rescue cannot guarantee the breed or full-grown adult size of any of the dogs or puppies in its care. Because many of these dogs were found as strays or are the result of irresponsible, unplanned breeding, we do not know the dog's exact background and can only list breed and size by our best educated guess. If exact breed and size are important to you, please consider adopting a dog from a specific breed rescue. Our goal is for our dogs to be adopted by people who will love and care for them forever for who they are - no matter what breed and size they turn out to be!

All dogs go to their new homes spayed or neutered, up to date on all shots, dewormed (although a second deworming may be required), started on heartworm and flea and tick preventative and sometimes microchipped.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Coal and I’m here to warm your heart! I am a three-month-old Pittie puppy full of life and love. I am jet black with a luxurious, shiny coat and totally wonky ears.  

I am a very quick learner, well on my way to being potty trained (I will signal you by running to the door and whimpering). It helps that I am highly treat- and food-motivated. I love running in the yard and am learning fetch. I take a few minutes to settle in my crate but am a good boy while you are gone and during the night. Sometimes I even go in my crate to take a puppy nap after a hard morning of playing. 

I like other big dogs and people, though I’m timid at first. However, little people would probably not fare well with me because I am so energetic and may knock them over. I am not very vocal. I would do great with a playmate my (eventual) adult size. Although I like small and senior dogs, I might be a little rambunctious for them.

Like most puppies, I’m still learning about inappropriate chewing, mouthiness, and leash manners. Please be patient with me! I’m still very young.

If you’re looking for a bright spark of energy and love, I’m your guy! 

Interested in adopting this dog? Visit our website (http://www.SecondCityCanineRescue.org) to fill out an application and to find out where this dog may be shown this weekend.

We love our dogs. We want happy lives for all of them and are looking for the home that provides the best fit for each dog’s individual needs. Please understand that there may be multiple families interested in this dog. Come to the show to find out if this dog is the right fit for you — it's helpful to bring all family members and current dogs. 

Also, please know that the breed mix listed is simply a guess. In most cases, we don’t know their background. We encourage you to base your decision on individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on our guess.

Please understand, we only adopt our animals out near the Chicagoland area. Questions? Email us at adoptions@sccrescue.org. Hope to see you become part of the SCCR family!

animal.description:
Meet Scooby! This is a special dog. Not only is he majestic in appearances, he loves water, fetching balls, and cuddling!

no small children or cats please! He is not aggressive towards small children but he's big and he lacks awareness of his size. So it is best to place him in a home that does not already have small children.

Scooby is a beautiful brindle boy, 3 years, approx 65 lbs. He is Potty trained and great in the house. Not destructive at all. Loves to chew on toys and balls. Has energy but settles in the house too with a toy. He is not reactive at all to other dogs. Nor is he aggressive. He may have some prey drive so no small dogs or cats. But he LOVES medium to large size dogs and loves to play with them!
Loves car rides. Used to play ball in the back of my Honda with me while driving. He is a bit afraid at first of new people, but not aggressive at all. Doesnt bark and does great in the crate with toys. Does not whine. 

We are crazy about him. Scooby loves loves to swim and play ball. He loves to lay on the float with you or fetch a ball

out in the water. This boy is so special and silly and will keep you laughing all day.

No small children please because it will make him nervous, Totally fine with dogs his size.

Scooby needs a pit or big dog knowledgeable home. Scooby had a rough start and missed some socialization skills as a pup. He has come a long way in many areas but he still is anxious in new settings. He would do ok with another dog with calm confidence. Unfortunately as he settled in, some prey instincts started showing up and for the safety of their other animals (little dogs and cats) we have to rehome him. We will assist with anything he needs and help the transition as much as possible. He is neutered, up to date on all vetting, crate trained, not at all destructive and loves to snuggle on the couch with you.

Please contact Michelle with your questions, michellelMFTLPC@gmail.com

The adoption fee is $400. He is up to date on vaccines according to age, has received proper deworming, and comes with additional dewormer if needed. This pet is microchipped, spayed/neutered, comes with 6 months of Heartworm preventative, and one month free trial of pet insurance if registered by adopter with insurance company. All animals receive a health certificate (stating that a licensed veterinarian saw the pet and deemed it healthy for travel, but is not a promise of perfect health.) Our transports are USDA certified and the cost of transport is included in adoption fee!

He/she may currently be fostered in Houston, Tx but will be traveling to the PNW as soon as he/she finds her perfect home or may be traveling to a foster in the PNW soon. 

Application link: https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/19753/generic

Please go to our website to see more about our rescue and what we do! We are very proud of our hard work in saving as many animals as we can, giving them what they need, and matching them with the right families.

animal.description:
***REQUIRES A FENCED IN YARD*** 

Say hello to Noelle! We got Noelle on Christmas day out of Louisiana after her owners were threatening to shoot her because they needed her gone immediately.

Noelle is about an 18 month old great Dane who is the definition of gentle giant. She is currently living in a circus of a Foster family that has 4 two-legged kids under the age of seven, three great Danes, cats, chickens, and goats! Noelle is perfect with all of them. She is attached at the hip to the second to youngest child, Harper, and sleeps in her bed at night. 

Prior to coming into rescue she lived a life outside, and because of that, she is heartworm positive and will need to remain on the rescue’s slow kill ivermectin and doxycycline regimen for the next year. 

Once in her foster home, she got the hang of everything almost immediately. And boy did she find a couch. She is very well mannered and willing to please. She could use some leash manners, they’re still working on that. At first she was a little pushy about food, but now that she’s been in foster care for a couple of weeks she understands that she’s never going to go without and has relaxed. She is not a people food beggar, unlike the other Danes in the household. And a squirt bottle is the perfect solution to redirect her from anything unwanted.

Her foster mom writes:

Noelle is a sweet Dane who came to us out of Louisiana. She’s playful and great with everyone including young kids, dogs, and cats. She can be shy at first, but quickly comes out of her shell in the presence of food and other dogs. We feel that she needs the companionship of another large dog to play with. She is very playful with a lot of energy to burn. A fenced in yard is a MUST for her. Noelle is also HW positive and will required continued treatment until she is negative. 

She has been spayed, had a gastropexy and is up to date on all vaccinations and chipped.

To read over our adoption requirements and apply to adopt Noelle please go to www.nwflgdr.com/adopt.

Noelle’s adoption fee is $400. 

ATTENTION: If you are applying from out of area or out of state, understand that if your application gets approved, you will be expected to pick up the dane in the location that he/she is being fostered. In addition, if the adoption does not work out, it is your responsibility to bring the dane safely back to us.

animal.description:
Courderoy came to us after he, his mom and brother were picked up by Animal Services running loose.  They were part of a family compound in which many dogs were in various conditions:  chained, in kennels and loose within a fenced area.  The people chose not to reclaim any of this sweet family which would have included fines for failure to have state required rabies vaccinations.  

Courderoy and his family all have the same sweet temperament.  His mom Latte, now Penny graduated and is living a wonderful life with her family in Dallas Georgia.  His brother Oscar was adopted by a family in Canada where he enjoys frolicking in the snow.  

Courderoy is a bulldog mixed with extra sweetness.  He is very friendly and loving.  He became a favorite at Riverbend, even with people who don't normally interact with our dogs.  

Courderoy is 55 lbs, and heartworm negative.  He is housetrained, crate trained, although he prefers cuddling with his person.  He knows sit, down, go to your spot, stay, leave it, give, come, off, and wait (for food and at doors).  

Courderoy is very loyal.  He loves to play ball and with anything that squeaks.  He enjoys a belly rub and considers that a reward for good behavior.  

Courderoy does not like loud boisterous people (especially high pitched), jangling keys, moving carts and heavy chains.  Obviously brings back some bad memories of his prior life.  

Courderoy has excellent house manners, is more of a couch potato than an athlete, although he does enjoy his playtimes in the fenced yard.

So keep any eye on the site for any animals being added as available for adoption as new animals are added everyday! We would recommend if you haven’t done so already that you submit a general online adoption application with us so it is on file for when you are ready to come out and adopt. The adoption counselors will be able to show you many that would be a good fit for your family. Animal House Shelter can not guarantee breed or breed mix of our adoptable animals. The animals are posted on the website as a breed or breed mix based on their physical characteristics they most resemble. We also can not guarantee the ages of our adoptable animals or how large puppies will be when fully grown.

weight:  
estimated age:  

These dogs are in the KENNEL at Small Miracles, you MUST apply IN PERSON

PLEASE READ INFORMATION BELOW:

This dog recently arrived and is just settling in.  If you are interested in adopting,  YOU MUST COME IN PERSON during adoption hours and fill out an application.  Adoption hours and address are viewable on the website at www.smallmiraclesrescue.org


---FAQ---

Is This Dog Currently Available?... This dog is available at the Small Miracles rescue facility in Ellicott City.  To submit an application, please come meet this dog in person.  You can bring your application with you, or you can fill one out when you come in.  Dogs will be removed from PetFinder only when they have an approved application or more than three (3) interested applicants.

Where did this dog come from?...  We rescue dogs from 100% kill shelters in West Virginia and on occasion from Kentucky.  On rare occasions we accept owner surrenders.  Due to the nature of the shelters they were rescued from, we often do not know the dogs' history.

How Old is this dog?...  We look at a dogs' teeth to estimate its age, and then the age is reevaluated by our veterinary staff when the dog is spayed/neutered.  If an age is not posted online, please feel free to inquire.

Is this dog Good With Kids?...  We occasionally know for sure if a dog is good with kids because it came from a home with kids.  This is rare.  We always suggest you bring your children in to meet the dog if you are seriously interested in adopting.  Dogs may like some kids and may dislike others.  Dogs are individuals, just like kids are.

Is this dog Housebroken?...  Advice from a veterinarian:  Even if a dog is housebroken at my house, it does not mean that it understands not to pee at someone else's house.  It ONLY understands not to pee at my house.  Some dogs make the connection that they should only pee outside.  Some must be retrained when they come home.  All we can tell you for sure is whether/or not a dog's crate is clean when we come to walk them in the AM.  All this means is that they are crate trained and waited to pee until we took them outside.

What is this dog's Temperament?...  We do not have a clear picture of a dog's temperament until we have allowed them to settle in for a few days.  Even then they are living in a shelter environment with many other dogs and a lot of daily activity.  It can be difficult to say a dog is "calm" or "nervous" when the shelter environment is playing a big role in that behavior.  We only rescue FRIENDLY dogs who have no known bite history.  If a dog is at Small Miracles, it likes people and has a good temperament.  We always suggest you meet the dog to see if it is the right fit for your lifestyle. 

What are your Fees?...  Base adoption fee is $325 for adult dogs and puppies.  To this, we add a $30 microchip fee, which we register for you, and a 6 month supply of heartworm preventative.  Heartworm preventative costs $40-60 depending on the weight of the dog.  This means that a large dog will total $405.00 and an extra large dog will total $415.00.

Why can't I adopt a FREE dog?...  Our adoption fee covers many procedures which cost much more for us then the amount we ask for from you. We spay/neuter all pets, and we give them their first round of vaccines (canine distemper, bordatella, Rabies if age appropriate).  At a typical vet clinic this would cost you $500 at minimum for the surgery, and each vaccine is roughly $35 each.  Even if your adopted dog does not have all of its shots due to the mandatory waiting period between booster shots, we offer vaccinations at the low cost of $20/shot.  We test all dogs for heartworm disease and tickborn illnesses such as Lymes.  We never euthanize a heartworm positive dog, and treatment routinely costs us $3000/dog.  We collect a fecal sample from every rescued dog and run a microscopic parasite test.  Any parasites found will be treated with two rounds of the appropriate dewormer.  We treat all dogs for fleas and ticks with Advantage.  If a dog has significant dental disease or "very dirty teeth", we will perform a dental cleaning when the dog has its spay/neuter surgery.  A dental cleaning with extractions would cost you upwards of $400-600 at your local vet clinic.

ALSO NOTE... Small Miracle is a 501(c)(3) charitable organization.  We survive off of our adoption fees and donations from the community.  We are a non-profit animal rescue and do not receive income from tax revenue as some county shelters do. 

For more information including Adoption Hours and Rescue Address, please visit our website at www.smallmiraclesrescue.org

Rusty is a two year old, chocolate lab mix.  Rusty was surrendered to our partner shelter in Louisiana.  He was found to be heartworm positive.  Rusty has gone through and completed his heartworm treatment.   He will be joining AHR's pack on January 30th!  

Rusty is a typical lab in that he has a lot of energy.  He loves humans, gets along well with other dogs.  He does like to chase kitties, as he has found this to be a fun game.  Rusty is working on his manners.  He is learning not to jump and how to walk well on a leash.  He is house trained.  He is crate trained, but the longer he is in a crate the more energy he has built up!   He would enjoy a active family.  


Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered.

animal.description:
Bolt was made to be your best friend. He's not a loner, he's a lover. His biggest goal in life is to figure out what you want him to do (and then do it), and when he succeeds, he celebrates by wiggling his entire body and nuzzling you to share his joy! His second biggest goal in life is to curl up beside you, mash his face into the side of your leg, and snore. 

Bolt's idea of a perfect day is anything that involves being where you are, really, whether it's showing off good behavior on a leash or keeping an eye on you as he dozes. His curiosity and attentiveness help him adjust to new situations like a pro, as long as there's someone around for him to take cues from -- he's a fast learner! Bolt also already understands basic manners, so with a little encouragement, he could be picking up new tricks in no time. 

One thing he doesn't need to learn how to do, though, is love you. He's already got that one down. Primary Color: Brindle Secondary Color: White Weight: 57.375lbs Age: 4yrs 2mths 3wks Animal has been Neutered

animal.description:
EXPERIENCED DACHSHUND OWNER ONLY!

Ezra is a mocha-colored mini, wire-haired dachshund who is an active 12 pound boy.

Ezra turns 11 years young in February 2021..He knows the commands “play by yourself”, “Go Hurry Up”, “Ezra Wait.” And “sit”. He is house/potty trained and walks well on a leash. His aim is to please his owner.

We feel he would be best suited with a female, no young children, and the only dog.

The only situation with Ezra is, he has a biting history, never bitten his person, but her friends. We feel this can be managed in different surroundings/ quieter home. You will also have to have experience with this dachshund behavior. A must!! Don’t just look at him and think he’s cute, there is that other side, that can land him in trouble.

Ezra’s ideal situation would be a woman owner who no longer works outside the home, who will take him for daily walks, play with him in a fenced yard, have space to play fetch with him in the house, and have few if any, visitors. Crating him when a visitor arrives or when you need to do an errand, is imperative; crating relieves his anxiety over new situations, and ensures his comfort.

Again we are asking for a phone interview before filling out an application.

Darby is a sweet boy who's only ~18-20# whose owner turned over to rescue because he was BLIND! He is such a sweet boy who just wants love, companionship, and a safe home to live!

Darby has "mature cataracts," so is blind according to our general Vet even though he's not that old. He is scheduled to be evaluated by our Eye Vet Specialist the week of 1/18/21 for an assessment/treatment plan (surgery?).

Sweet Darby was initially unsettled and afraid he would be left and clinged on to his foster parent's neck - so endearing and heartbreaking at the same time. He's is sooooo SWEET and loving and GRATEFUL he is loved and being well taken care of by his foster and rescue!

Darby is current on vaccinations, heartworm/fecal tested and negative, neutered, and microchipped.

WE TOOK THIS SWEET BOY BECAUSE HE NEEDED US

METRO ATLANTA ONLY

Email

passionforanimals5017@gmail.com

if interested in SWEET Darby

animal.description:
This pupper originally landed at HSNBA in September of 2020 with a badly mangled leg. He got his leg amputated with our friends at Animal Medical Center and also found his new home. Sadly, he somehow ended up in a high kill shelter in Galveston and when AMC heard about THAT they went and picked him up! Now we are all working together to find a new FOREVER home! 
Is anyone looking for a high energy, beautiful pup?! He's only got 3 legs, but he's got more heart than most dogs. All he needs is someone who has the time and patience to train and work with him. He wants and deserves a good forever home!HSNBA lists all animals online from the moment of intake, and our listings are updated automatically every midnight. Some of these animals may not be available for adoption at this moment, but you can always call the shelter at 830-629-5287 for clarification on the adoption process or the animal's current status.

animal.description: Brooklyn is full of personality. She is an active gal with lots of love to give. A home with no small children would be better for her. As for other dogs, we feel it would be best if Brooklyn were the only dog in the house. She seems to have never learned how to interact with other dogs, so when she is around them she gets too worked up. Training would be a good thing for Brooklyn. It is important to note that during her evaluation, Brooklyn did have some issues when presented with a pig's ear. It seemed workable, and an experienced trainer could help teach her that there is no worry in high value treats being taken away. Brooklyn is the kind of girl who makes her presence known, but don't let her fool you, she is a real sweetheart.

animal.description: Elrond is a nice, one and a half year old mixed breed dog. This handsome boy is deaf and will need a special someone who is interested in learning how to train and share their life with a deaf dog. Deaf dogs can make wonderful pets. They can be just as loving and well behaved as a hearing dog, they just need someone committed to learning how to train them. If you are interested in opening your heart and your home to a deaf dog go online and check out Deaf Dog Education Action Fund. Their site gives loads of good information about living with a deaf dog. Elrond's adoption includes neutering, microchipping and up to date shots.For more information about this animal or our adoption process please visit our website at SouthJerseyRegionalAnimalShelter.org
